The Parliament did not support the amendment liberating Tymoshenko
Ukraine’s parliament has rejected a proposal to repeal a section of the criminal code that convicted opposition leader Yulia Tymoshenko.
The amendment, which would pave the way for the release of the imprisoned ex-prime minister, was rejected by MEPs at the second reading of the proposal to reduce the penalties for economic crimes.
In October, Tymoshenko was sentenced to seven years in prison for concluding an allegedly unfavourable contract with Russia for the purchase of natural gas.
The verdict is not final, and the appeal is due to be heard by the court in December.
Tymoshenko calls the verdict a political revenge of the regime, and suspicions of court bias have sparked a trial in the West as well.
The motion to remove from the Criminal Code section 365, on the basis of which the ex-prime minister was convicted, was supported by 147 deputies in the vote.
It needed 226 votes to pass.
