The menu of an obese child: no breakfast and dinner sausages
More than a third of children aged 9 to 13 have problems with being overweight, with 9% of schoolchildren being overweight and 5% of children being obese.
Obese children mostly come from families with unhealthy lifestyles, according to a recent survey.
Once again, it shows how important the environment in which a person grows up and the patterns with which he is surrounded is for the healthy development of the person.
For example, cold cuts appear on the tables of obese children up to half more often than in families of children with normal weight.
Fried French fries had for dinner the day before the research associated with the awareness event called Obesity is not a coincidence more than 19 percent of obese.
It is also not the custom for fat families to play sports, but this applies to most families of today's schoolchildren - only 15% of children answered that their parents find time for active movement at least once a week.
A survey of 900 children
The survey took place at the end of last year's school year and was attended by almost 900 children from primary schools from all over the Czech Republic.
It was the second year of the Obesity is Not a Coincidence event, which is supported by the General Health Insurance Company and Unilever.
So far, more than 12 thousand schoolchildren from 4th to 8th grades have participated in the project.
Proper nutrition and sufficient exercise in the family is one of the determining factors, which causes a dramatically increasing number of children who are overweight or even obese.
“Only half of the respondents, for example, said that they eat five times a day in the mode of breakfast-breakfast-lunch-lunch-dinner, which is one of the basic prerequisites for proper nutrition,” reads one of the results of the survey.
Without breakfast and evening sausage
Experts point out that for a healthy development are essential and relative details, which include the regular time of family breakfasts.
In the Czech Republic, only 23 percent of families eat breakfast at the same time.
In most families, everyone eats breakfast alone.
And the worst was the finding that a tenth of households do not eat breakfast at all.
Breakfast is the basis of a proper daily diet.
The questionnaire showed that in families of obese children, unhealthy fries are consumed much more often.
Almost everyone - regardless of weight - drinks sweet lemonade every day (70 percent).
Although more than 40 percent of children regularly participate in sports, the result for their parents was less than half - 15 percent.
Set up your own diet
Another part of the survey allowed selected children (204 boys and 172 girls from 13 schools) to build their own menu according to their own taste and opinion.
"The dietary preferences of Czech children aged 12 to 15 are far from ideal in terms of healthy nutrition."
Among their favorite dishes are a lot of floury, meaty and sweet dishes.
"The great popularity of sweet lemonades is particularly alarming," the survey's final report said.
For lunch, the main meal was won by pasta just above poultry.
But the children practically did not want legumes at all, and the popularity of fish and midday vegetable dishes is also low.
Incline to health
At the same time, the survey showed that children are willing to adjust their eating habits if they get the right information.
"In the control group of survey participants who completed the questionnaire after the end of the lecture Obesity is not a coincidence, in many cases there was a significant shift in preferences towards the principles of healthy nutrition," the project's results say.
It was striking, for example, in sweet lemonades, where more children would start to prefer ordinary water.
Children were also much more likely to cross out poultry and fish as the main meal of the day and limit sweet foods and dumplings.
Stylist must also be a good psychologist, say pros
In the introductory article about how stylists learn, I complained so much that there was a lot of it already in the introductory lessons.
I had no idea what was going to happen next.
Lectures by three professionals from the field, dressing of problematic characters and a seminar on how to go on stage.
And it's gonna get worse.
The closer to the final exam, the more information and practical tasks await us.
And even though the course is held every Saturday and Sunday, it is really “stunned”.
This time, Director Alenka and I discussed (there is not a single boy in the course) how to dress a woman who does not have a perfectly symmetrical figure.
Such are the vast majority.
Someone has a short neck, someone has a boyish figure without proper curves, and someone is overweight.
The stylist must know how to optically soften wide shoulders, lengthen the neck or deliver the necessary curves.
We were given tips for a woman like Jennifer Lopez, i.e. bigger breasts and hips and a narrow waist, to emphasize the figure nicely and at the same time not to dress the woman too provocatively.
For example, if the difference between the waist and the hips is such that the skirt or pants really do not fit, then it is worth having at least one such piece made to measure.
You will definitely not regret it, because perfectly fitting clothes are priceless.
You will feel much better in a tailored skirt than in one that constantly moves, folds, reclines at the waist and the like.
The boy’s character can afford to wear clothes with lashes, applications, embroidery or picking.
Of course, there are a lot of such information and types of characters, so I am glad that I have a whole week to sort all the information in my head.
And I'm still afraid that, given the homework assignment, it's too much.
Each of the students received an assigned celebrity, with whom she has to come up with two outfits: day and evening.
We must take into account the current appearance, fashion style of the person and the type of figure.
I'll "dress" Miranda Kerr, maybe you know her from the Victoria's Secret campaigns.
In the spirit of exultation, for me personally definitely better than Britney Spears, Christina Aguilera, who recently gained perhaps a hundred pounds (please take into account the exaggeration), or young Selena Gomez.
Clothes must be cut from magazines or searched on the Internet and printed and then graphically processed.
Moodboard, as the whole result is called, will then express our personal style and relationship to graphic design.
Thinking about the graphic side of styling is also important.
The stylist does not only wear physically, but also creates, for example, so-called product pages in magazines (for a specific task, for example, trendy handbags, coats, etc.).
This was told to us by the stylist and designer Mario Kamen<0xC3><0xAD>k.
But not until Sunday.
The stylist must have a general overview
Saturday’s lecture was packed with information about the types of characters and was enriched by three guests from the industry.
Stylist Honza Pokorn<0xC3><0xBD>, fashion designer Jakub Polanka and fashion photographer Ben Ren<0xC4><0x8D>.
Jakub reminded us that fashion is an illusion and a stylist should be able to use it.
And a skillful stylist can work with one piece of clothing differently.
Variability is key in this case.
For example, such a trench coat (or if you originally want trenchcoat) can be worn classically over jeans and a T-shirt as a cloak, but you can also wear it on a bare body, put on a boat and take a picture as a dress.
Or just roll up your sleeves or collars and the whole look looks different.
"Play with it," he said.
But what I appreciated the most was the following advice: "You need to know the rules perfectly for the job."
"Then you can start breaking them," Jacob said.
Finally, I understand why we are crushing all the lessons, what to combine with, why, why, when we sometimes see something different in fashion magazines.
Not to mention the shows.
Thanks to the photographer Ben, I know that the stylist must have prepared many more variants of clothes than how many can be photographed.
So for a fashion story that will have ten pages (i.e. ten outfits), I have to be ready to "set up" at least fifteen.
And also that in the photo the clothes look and work in combination with other pieces sometimes completely different than in reality.
This is what we need to consider when designing an outfit.
That image and style sometimes makes up half the success was confirmed to us by Honza Pokorn<0xC3><0xBD>.
Just look at Madonna, who is not exactly a miracle singer, but her image and marketing have made her a world star.
In the Czech Republic, the approach to using the services of stylists is rather cold.
Even familiar faces sometimes consider it useless (it is enough that I know something, the way I look at it is secondary).
And if someone already lets us create styling, then we should count on the fact that they will most likely dictate a completely different (smaller) size than they really have.
Then you have to google and find out if the tabloid did not write about the fact that the celebrity has lost weight and so on.
Honza and Mario on Sunday put on our hearts that the stylist is not enough to orientate in fashion and know how to put together an outfit.
In his work, he primarily communicates with the people he dresses, so it is important to be a good psychologist.
To be able to judge people, not to encourage yourself, to stand up for your opinion.
"When a manager orders you to sort out her wardrobe and fill it with nice pieces, you can't throw out the whole closet and say, 'Oh, my God, that's terrible.'"
"Find at least a few things to praise and recommend what you can wear," Mario says.
He also specifically showed us what all must contain the so-called "placement", or bag on the site.
It is the one that you turn on around your waist and you have all the necessary proprieties with you.
In addition to bright things such as scissors, a hair roller or closing pins, there is also a nylon thread (with it the stylist helps when photographing products such as handbags or hats), special clips to fasten the back of the clothes, if it is larger (pin or other clamp is not allowed), the ponytail would be removed.
In order not only to listen, but also to practically try something, we learned how to properly fit shoes.
Even when shooting in a studio where there is a flat surface, the sole could be damaged, let alone outside.
And so we bonded and bonded.
We must not touch our shoes with scissors, so that they do not accidentally get damaged.
It really does require skill.
Mario pleased me when my creation without reservations praised.
This skill is not really my friend.
This is only a small fraction of what we heard about the second weekend of the course.
It is becoming increasingly clear to me that doing styling on a professional level is really not a walk in the rose garden, no matter who says what they want.
In Need for Speed: The Run, it races across America.
Testimonials
Originally carefree driving due to a series of completely unnecessary scoundrel mistakes turns into a routine morning trip to the ramp.
The ambition was largely fulfilled, but it was useless when no one seemed to want to do anything extra.
The new installment, subtitled The Run, raised high expectations for the release.
He promised that the old Need for Speed racing series would once again move a bit in a new direction, and from playable demonstrations it seemed like a game that would not have to be just in number in the action racing genre.
We were also curious to see how the inserted passages will turn out, in which the main character gets out of the car and runs on his own.
However, as with the NFS series, many of the results are a bit different than we expected.
These are potentially decent arcade races, but the whole drags down a few unnecessary mistakes that have been appearing in the series for more or less several years.
So these are not actually mistakes, but rather a manifestation of a kind of incomprehensible laziness of developers.
The adventure begins very well.
You are introduced to a story whose main character Jack has certain problems of a personal nature and as a solution is offered to participate in an illegal race across America.
Get behind the wheel on the west coast of San Francisco and your task is to arrive first in New York.
The idea brings with it several interesting elements.
The route is divided into ten stages, and then into more than fifty races.
It follows that each race is on a different track and the stages are set in different, sufficiently different and interesting environments.
It doesn’t feel like the game is always offering the same thing.
In addition, some of the environments are very nice to look at, although the technical level of the graphics corresponds to the previous parts of the series.
So it's nothing world-class.
But driving across deserts, autumn landscapes or high in the snowy mountains looks visually very pleasant.
Moreover, the races are from time to time enriched by some unusual element.
In the desert, for example, you become entangled in a sandstorm, which significantly reduces visibility.
On the other hand, in the mountains you have to be careful not to fall into an avalanche.
In addition, the individual races are quite well planted behind each other.
There are only a few types, but that’s enough.
For a while, you try to overtake the required number of opponents (basically a classic race), then you catch up with the time (classic fight with stopwatches) and then a duel with a single opponent is waiting for you.
From time to time, the police will get involved in this, which makes all your efforts even more unpleasant.
The novelty is the passages outside the car.
It’s more like an interactive animation where Jack usually runs away from someone and you have to help him by pressing the right buttons at the right times.
Nothing complicated.
It is surprising, however, that there are far fewer of these passages in the game than you would expect (perhaps even just three).
In the end, however, it is to the benefit of the matter, because this element does not have a chance to become annoying and in the context of the above, it belongs to the elements that diversify the game.
The driving model follows in the footsteps of the previous parts.
This means that today it is definitely not much, but it can not be said that it would be a negative.
If you are looking for a realistic simulation, you will have to look elsewhere.
But the more active racing concept of the local driving model still suits quite well, although we would be able to find a better one in the competition.
So far everything is in perfect order.
Problems begin to appear after a while.
Contrary to the model of the road, the model is no longer very good.
From a game of this type, we do not expect it to calculate complex deformations and collisions, but if you have no idea how your car will behave before practically any impact on any object, then perhaps everything is not quite all right.
Typically, if you overtake or pass cars in normal traffic, sometimes you only lick each other slightly, but at other times your car will end up in a wild pirouette in an almost identical situation.
Or even attack directly.
Thanks to the system of restarts, it does not really matter, but it will defuse you reliably.
Restarts are designed so that if you get crushed or go far off track, the game throws you back to the last catch point on the track.
Only five restarts are available in each race.
When you run out of them, you have to start the race again from the beginning.
So it’s more of a help in case something doesn’t work out than if you could rely on them explicitly.
Sometimes even restarts do not help, they are solved only by the need to learn a given section of the race by heart.
The big drawback of the game is that the same things often happen in the same places.
Some corners, for example, need to be driven in a specific way, otherwise you simply cannot fit into them.
Other times you will meet "civilian" cars at a given place always in the same configuration, whether you arrive there first, fifth, five seconds earlier or a minute later.
This is especially annoying in situations where you see an opponent passing between two cars in front of you, while when you get there, the cars are already in such a position that you have to detour or brake them.
It does not matter when you reach them, because it is "counted" so that the situation always occurs right in front of your nose.
Rivals have another advantage.
Throughout the game you will come across several places where, again, regardless of the time, you will always be overtaken by the same opponent in the same place.
This is most striking at the end of the game on a long bridge, where you go in the opposite direction.
The enemy must get there before you, apparently, at any cost.
When it goes in front of you, it worsens your view of the cars in front of you, so at first you spread out quite a few times.
You can understand the intention to make the game more exciting and adrenaline, but the execution is so obvious that it reliably quickly disgusts you.
And it's a pity, because despite the simple driving model, playing is fun and at times even so action that sometimes you literally do not have time to watch where everything flies.
And it doesn’t really matter if the concept with fifty unique tracks, arranging races so that boredom doesn’t stand a chance, or whatever.
An unusual idea is to exchange cars during races.
You need to pay attention to the gas stations on the roads, because that is where you can change the car, although in the vast majority of cases you will be enough with what you have right now.
Cars are divided into three categories.
Sportsmen are suitable for urban areas, strong American bumps on straight highways and exotic supersports for technical riding, for example, on winding mountain roads.
The main story mode goes hand in hand with the challenge mode, which are races in individual locations that you know from the story.
Here you get not only medals, but also experience points to your profile, which is common to challenges and story.
For gaining a higher level of the driver, various items are unlocked: starting with cars and ending with backgrounds for the profile.
It is also connected to the Autolog online feature, which compares your results with other players and provides additional community features.
One of the other hard-to-understand kicks is the situation from the last race in the story.
Your car will take you to the subway tunnel (let's go), where you drive it in the dark on the tracks (let's go).
On the speedometer, the figures between 150 and 200 km/h (maybe) flash, and in this, a subway set will come crashing in from behind and crush you uncompromisingly.
In the editorial office, we will probably have a few more days of discussion about whether no one really thought a bit when creating the game, or whether the authors think that we are really such big idiots.
The technical side of the game is nothing special, but at least the overall visual impression is in most cases very pleasant and in some cases even great.
It freezes in such a way that in some of the more tense moments the shooting decreases, and in some cases quite tragically.
However, this is especially true for a crash with a larger number of participants, when smooth shooting would not be useful for you anyway.
The sound is fine and the soundtrack is a matter of taste.
In an attempt to appeal to the widest possible range of a rather younger audience, a soundtrack from the category "every dog is different", but it can be assumed that someone will not buy the game just because of listening to music.
Need for Speed: The Run is a great game.
If the game avoided completely unnecessary errors, then we would not be afraid to say that The Run is the best work of the NFS over the past few years.
This is how the game feels unfinished.
Fun is certainly nice, but be prepared for the fact that mistakes will crush you in the eye with the power of airport spotlights.
