Ambassador to the EU Vice-President:
Czechs have a reputation for being negative and Eurosceptic
"The Lisbon Treaty has quite significantly upset the balance between the various institutions."
"I didn't expect it to be such a hard war."
"It will take five or six years before the situation calms down and all the players get used to their new roles," Czech Ambassador to the European Union Milena Vicenová began her lecture at the Faculty of Law.
As far as she takes her motto "Intelligibly and openly about Europe" seriously, she showed in the first part of the lecture, when she managed to describe individual EU institutions and their relations in such a clear and understandable way that many lecturers from the Faculty of Law of the Charles University could envy her.
Vicen also praised the work of the new permanent President of the European Council, Herman Van Rompuy:
"At first there was criticism that he was a diminutive, that he was a gray official, that he could not play any role, and I must say that everyone was blown away, that the role was excellent."
"He is a man who listens to the 27 member states, communicates well with them and has a clear vision of where the European Union should go."
She then explained the new post of High Representative for Foreign Affairs and Security Policy as an answer to the question: "Who is this European Union? Which phone number should I call?", i.e. as an important step towards unification and greater readability of EU policy towards countries such as China or India.
Nobody wants to ban us from cheeses
Vicenová also devoted herself to the agenda that the European Council has lived, lives and will live in the near future.
She called the Czech Presidency a success.
The Czechs solved the coming financial crisis, solved the gas crisis or organized a summit for the Eastern Partnership.
She described the fall of the government at that time as a big negative, which damaged the Czech Republic very badly.
The Czech representation in the EU is currently very busy.
In the words of the Ambassador, "the fact of the matter" was not only the Presidency, but also the subsequent financial crisis, which is still being addressed today.
Moreover, the new seven-year budget of the Union still has to be approved, which is complicated by the current economic situation.
Whether the budget will be lean and economical, which sectors will be preferred, which countries will be supported more and which less, is all on the agenda for the next negotiations.
The ambassador also recalled her main slogans, with which she came to Brussels: "About Europe intelligibly".
"I really don't like ugly abbreviations, foreign words, a snub that no one understands.
How can a citizen understand that curved or round cucumbers, bananas of different sizes are not really invented in Brussels, or that someone really has to ban us from cheeses.
He also wants to make better use of the EU environment and get more Czechs into European institutions.
We have a multi-speed Europe.
According to the ambassador, the Czechs have a reputation of Eurosceptics and people who pay more attention to the negative than the positive aspects of the matter.
Moreover, it regrets the low representation of Czechs in European institutions.
According to her, many factors are to blame, such as the modesty of our candidates, their inability to write motivational letters, but also low support from the Czech side.
In addition to the successful Czech Presidency, it highlighted the strength and cooperation of the Visegrad Four.
"Believe me, when a Pole and a Hungarian come to me and a Slovak approaches, the Frenchman next to me will say: 'Hey, what are you meeting there, what is your Visegrad Four?' and he does not look excited about it at all."
In the future, according to Vicenová, the EU will mainly face new tough rules for the budgetary policies of the member states.
He sees as very real the concept of a two-speed, if not multi-speed Europe, rather than a new "European federation".
“We have countries in the eurozone and countries outside the eurozone.”
"We have the Schengen area, we already have the institute of enhanced cooperation."
"For the first time, it has been said that only the countries that want to cooperate, and those that don't, should stay away."
"There will be more of these institutes, and it will be a strong two-speed Europe," Vicen said.
In this regard, she also appreciated the role of the Czech Republic and Herman Van Rompuy in promoting the principle that all topics affecting the whole of the Union should be discussed between all Member States, not just between euro area countries.
Brand story:
IBM Innovator Begins Second Century of Its Existence
If someone were looking for the word that most accurately expresses IBM’s strategy, the closest would probably be “long-term.”
For the general public, IBM is a symbol of the technological revolution, it is a company perceived as very present, and yet a hundred years have passed since its foundation.
The foundation for this longevity was laid by the company’s first CEO, visionary Thomas J. Watson Sr.
He has already coined the slogan that many of the world’s problems can be easily solved if people are willing to think.
His slogan "Think!" became the imprint around which the life of the future giant will unfold (and also the name of an internal magazine that began to be published at IBM in 1935).
