History of IBM: From cheese slicer to space flight
IBM (International Business Machines) was founded in New York a hundred years ago, originally with the complex name of Computing Tabulating Recording Corporation.
IBM took over the name in 1924 – originally a brand used for the company’s branches in Canada and South America.
The basis for the later IBM was given by the merger of four companies whose history dates back to the eighties of the nineteenth century.
They owned technologies such as the famous "pawns", i.e. clocks recording employees' arrival and departure.
The architect of the new company was businessman Charles Ranlett Flint, who also chaired the company’s supervisory board until 1930.
Flint hired the head of a rival firm, Thomas J. Watson, to help him run the company.
The leader then overshadowed the founders of IBM - Watson's ideas are still built on an invincible corporate culture and identity.
Watson ran the company until 1952.
IBM, as its name suggests, began with the production and sale of all kinds of machines for business - from meat and cheese slicers to cash registers.
During Watson’s first four years in charge, sales doubled to $9 million, and the company began a large-scale expansion to all continents.
Watson was so indispensable to the company that after nearly forty years in the executive chair, he was replaced by his son, Thomas Watson Junior.
Under his leadership, IBM began to work on the development of artificial intelligence, developed the first programming language.
In the 1960s, people and computers from IBM helped NASA control flights to space - to Mercury, Saturn, and in 1969, the famous man's flight to the moon.
In 1964, IBM developed the first family of computers, the IBM System/360 series.
The classic “dish” that set the computer standard of the time, the IBM 5150, came to market in 1981.
Twenty years later, IBM sold its PC business to Lenovo in China, bought the consulting arm of PricewaterhouseCoopers, and began to focus on high-value consulting and services.
The strategy that IBM has been paying off over the last three years is the concept of Smarter Planet, a “smarter planet”.
Its aim is to make smart use of technology in areas that have not been planned yet and to improve the situation, for example, in transport or city administration.
For commerce, IBM recently introduced the “Smarter Commerce” platform, which helps traders manage the entire commercial cycle.
IBM has a strong history in the country.
It established its branch in what was then Czechoslovakia in 1932 as the first country in Central and Eastern Europe.
Today, in addition to IBM, the Czech Republic also operates a strategic outsourcing center in Brno.
The Centre for Central and Eastern Europe is based in Prague and there is also a world-class research team dealing with voice recognition.
