How Travel Prices Have Evolved Since 1989
Until 1989, only five state travel agencies were allowed in Czechoslovakia: <0xC4><0x8C>edok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
At that time, travel agencies sold only tours to the countries of the socialist bloc, as travel to the west was very limited.
Czech tourists travelled to the GDR (German Democratic Republic), the Soviet Union (Sochi on the Black Sea), Bulgaria, Romania (both to the Black Sea) and Hungary (Balaton).
The bright exception was the period from 1962 to 1972, when it was possible to travel to Yugoslavia, but then the Yugoslav regime leaned towards the West and the trips of Czech tourists to Yugoslavia were subsequently very limited.
The great paradox of the socialist era was that the citizens of the socialist bloc (i.e. also the Czechoslovaks) were not allowed to travel individually freely even within socialist countries.
If a citizen of Czechoslovakia wanted to travel individually to, for example, Poland or the Soviet Union, he needed an invitation letter from this country, otherwise an individual trip was not possible.
Travel agencies at that time also offered trips to the West, but it was necessary to stand in line overnight with a sleeping bag or have "good friends" in the travel agency.
Even so, it was not won.
The so-called foreign exchange promise, which was a condition for travel to the West, was not given to “politically unreliable people” who could not travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a freely convertible currency, so it was impossible to obtain funds (Western currency) for the journey to the West without a foreign exchange promise.
However, the Czechs most often spent their holidays in the country, which resulted in a large number of cottages and cottages, which the Czechs bought and this custom survives to this day.
The Czech Republic has experienced a real revolution since 1989.
While until 1989 holidays in the GDR or Bulgaria were our maximum, last year Czechs spent 4.5 million holidays abroad in countries around the world.
A huge paradox that we are no longer aware of today is that it was not possible to travel freely to the most popular Croatia for us today until 1989, as it was part of Yugoslavia at that time.
In the early 1990s, visa requirements were lifted in neighbouring Western European countries, triggering a huge wave of short-term visits mainly to Austria’s Vienna and Germany.
The Czechoslovaks could not get enough of trips to the West for a long time, everyone wanted to see there at least for a moment.
For example, in Paris, the trips of Czechs in parks in tents were sleeping, because our income at that time did not allow us to pay for a hotel or a guesthouse.
A typical feature of travelling in Bohemia at this time was the transportation of own food, canned food, salami, etc., in order to save money.
Another important moment was the introduction of the freely convertible Czech crown, which allowed our tourists to finally buy the western currency freely after many decades.
However, our standard of living and, with it, average wages rose, which resulted in another important moment around 1997.
Due to the increased demand for travel, travel agencies have started to regularly prepare trips by charter airlines since 1997, which has made air travel incredibly cheaper due to the possibility of contracting volume discounts compared to the past.
At the end of the 1990s, Czechs had visa-free access to practically all developed countries in the world, except the USA, which further facilitated our travel.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolutionary travel occurred in 2000, when, thanks to considerable demand, the first direct charter flight from the Czech Republic to exotics was to Thailand.
Since this year, direct charters with Czech tourists have been flying to warm distant countries every year, and this winter will fly directly from the Czech Republic to twelve exotic destinations.
Exotic countries are currently visited by about 100 thousand Czechs a year!
Another interesting moment in this period, which symbolizes our post-revolutionary development, came in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the USA abolished visas for Czech tourists, and thus our country finally ranked among the most developed countries in the world.
In 2008, for the first time in history, Czechs spent more than half of their holidays abroad (50.3%) and for the first time in history spent more than 15 thousand CZK per person for one foreign holiday, including the cost of the place of stay.
