Massacre on a personal level
Peter Englund’s emotionally powerful new book, The Beauty and the Sorrow: An Intimate History of the First World War, begins with a long list of characters that make you dizzy.
One tip on how to behave at that moment: Carefully tear out this page and make a bookmark out of it.
You will get acquainted with all the people in Mr. Englund's novel, and this list will serve as a navigation - as a kind of beacon - in moments when, like men and women in the story, you will feel confused and lost in various situations.
Mr. Englund is a Swedish historian and journalist.
He is also a new deputy at the Swedish Academy, which awards the Nobel Prize in Literature.
The book we are talking about here is very unusual - the author himself describes it, quite aptly, as an "antihistoric work".
It contains several well-known names, important treaties or famous battles, on the contrary, it almost lacks ambassadors, energetic journalists and debates about tactics and equipment.
It is not so much a book about what happened, the author explains, as rather "a book about what it was like". It deals mainly with "feelings, impressions, experiences and moods".
"Beauty and Grief" combines the war experiences of 20 more or less dozen men and women, on both sides of the barricade, from female students and botanists to climbers, doctors, ambulance drivers and officials.
Some of these people will become heroes.
Others become prisoners of war, lose limbs, go insane, or die.
Their lives flicker like the flames of candles lit in a church - new ones are added to the tangle of destinies, while others are extinguished.
Mr. Englund's book differs from classic historical novels.
It modifies the notion that the First World War was all about the terrible trench battles on the Western Front.
"Beauty and Grief" deftly explores other places where war dramas took place: the Alps, the Balkans, the Eastern Front, Mesopotamia, East Africa.
Soldiers in this book deal with the problems of falling on them bee nests, having to spend Christmas in the shadow of the pyramids or struggling with the presence of flies tse-tse.
Almost from the beginning it is a very touching read.
War engulfs people's lives like some kind of natural disaster, like Hurricane Katrina smelling of gunpowder.
When cannon fire starts to sound in the distance and you are a woman who is at home with your children, will you run away or will you stay?
Who's really coming?
Almost no one understands what is happening, not even why the whole war was unleashed.
"The vacuum created by a lack of facts," observed Mr. Englund, "was filled with conjectures, conjectures, hopes, fears, prejudices, conspiracy theories, dreams, nightmares, and rumours."
"Beauty and Grief" follows the stories of individuals such as Florence Farmborough, an English nurse in the Russian army, and Richard Stumpf, a young sailor serving in the German fleet.
Their stories are mostly taken from biographies, letters and other already published materials.
The descriptions of their lives may sound scary and engaging, but thanks to the incorporation of small moments and details, they are absolutely vivid and believable.
Many of them talk about suffering and coping with it.
In the story of a German student, the author says: "Replacements, substitutes everywhere."
"Coffee substitute, aluminum imitation, rubber imitation, paper bandages, wooden buttons."
It goes even further and describes food substitutes in Germany.
It mentions "meat made from pressed rice cooked in sheep's fat (and supplemented with fake bone from wood), tobacco from dried roots and dried potato skins, shoes with wooden soles".
There were 837 registered substitutes for meat in the production of sausages and 511 registered substitutes for coffee.
Some stories are about honor and bravery.
An American finds an inner impulse to savagery and brutality, and declares of the war: "In the end, you will understand that this is human nature. Not to sit in comfortable chairs with a cigarette and whiskey, an evening newspaper or a good book, and pretend that this mask of yours represents civilization, and that there is no trace of me behind it.
On the contrary, the British soldier realizes that he will most likely die soon, and no one will even notice, let alone mourn.
“When a person finally comes to terms with sacrificing himself, he would at least expect it to happen in front of a grateful audience,” he writes.
Instead, he feels like a “convict who will be hanged in secret.”
Other remarks concern the departure of old Europe and the emergence of new horrors.
“Conflict has increasingly become an economic competition and a competitive struggle,” writes Mr. Englund, “a war between factories.”
He captured what he calls "a new kind of beast of the coming century: a eloquent and ideologically committed mass murderer in a tailor-made dress who carries out his bloodshed without rising from the table."
People behave completely unexpectedly, meanness alternates with heroism.
Mr. Englund also describes soldiers who deliberately tried to catch a venereal disease from prostitutes in order to avoid service at the front.
“The most grotesque example of this behavior was the trade in gonococcal pus, which soldiers shopped for and scrubbed their genitals with in the hope of ending up in a hospital,” he writes.
"The most desperate would rub it in their eyes, which often blinded them for the rest of their lives."
In this translation from Swedish by Peter Graves, Mr. Englund's prose is brisk but not flamboyant, which fits perfectly with his human theme.
In dozens of small outputs, he captures the way in which the war "has unleashed utterly unmanageable forces: extreme nationalism, social revolution, religious hatred".
People are starting to wonder why their leaders are forcing them to fight.
The best books on the First World War mostly worked with hints, such as "World War I and Modern Memories" by Paul Fussell or novels such as "On the Western Front Peace" by Erich Maria Remarque.
Mr. Englund prefers an unconventional concept.
His book has the most devastating ending that is unprecedented in popular scholarly literature.
But I will not reveal it to you.
However, you will feel as if the author suddenly jumped out of the book, ripped the page from the list of heroes from your hand and lit it on fire.
After a previous mistake, this time for a minute exactly scheduled raids
It was attended by hundreds of police officers, some wearing helmets used in street riots.
The night from Monday to Tuesday was chosen because by that time Zuccotti Park should be almost empty.
No one knew about the event except a few high-ranking officers. The others were first told that it was an exercise.
Police Commissioner Raymond W. Kelly was at the forefront of the action, whose presence highlighted how many problems the police department had to face during the operation.
Cases in recent weeks, such as the use of pepper sprays against demonstrators, were not allowed to be repeated, in violation of the rules of separation and, moreover, a wave of public sympathy spilled over to the squatters.
Therefore, a police operation to clear the Zuccotti Park of demonstrators was launched after two weeks of careful planning and exercise.
The leaders were inspired by the operations that took place in other cities.
A massive emergency behavior exercise was held in the Randalls Island area, which was in preparation for an event in Zuccotti Park.
Leaders have stepped up so-called riot-control training — counterterrorism measures involving the rapid movement of large numbers of police — with a focus on the Lower Manhattan metropolitan area.
The last part of the training took place on Monday night, on the Manhattan side of the East River.
The orders to move to the park came literally “at the last minute,” said someone to whom the action was originally explained only as “exercise.”
“I know a few police officers who have also been called to this action, and no one has told them that they are going to Zuccotti Park,” said the person, who spoke only on condition of anonymity.
"Only the highest-ranking members of the department knew about going to Zuccotti Park."
One of the reasons for the secrecy was the lesson the city had already learned.
On October 14, the city officials planned to clear the park, but then withdrew from the plan, because as soon as the demonstrators heard about it, they rushed hundreds of them to the park before the operation began.
Tuesday's event was attended by police officers from various units, including intervention groups from around the area - dozens of police officers who are routinely used to strengthen neighborhoods with higher crime rates.
Mr. Kelly explained that during the day a large number of people come and go to the park, so one hour at night was the ideal time to start the event.
"It was appropriate to do this at a time when there would be as few people as possible in the park," he said.
By the time the troops left, they had lined up at the intersection of Pike Slip and Franklin D. Roosevelt Drive, near the Manhattan Bridge, trucks of emergency units with arc lamps and amplions.
The lights and the recorded message roaring from the amplions frightened many demonstrators.
When members of the riot police entered the park in their blue windbreakers, many of the demonstrators packed their belongings and left.
Police say she did not touch a single tent until 1:45 a.m., giving protesters time to pack their belongings.
Other teams of police officers were seen gathering on the edge of the park to break into it if any arrests were needed.
Reporters were forced to leave the park.
Police chief spokesman Paul J. Browne said it was for their own safety.
However, many journalists are of the opinion that the police wanted to prevent them from seeing her troops in action, and in addition, some police officers were rude to them.
Mr. Browne claimed that the TV cars on Church Street along the park's western border could shoot without problems.
The police moved westward, interspersed with a dense entanglement of protesters' personal belongings, including luggage and plastic bags full of clothing, followed by teams from the hygiene department, who immediately gathered up what was left of the park.
Some protestors who refused to move were dragged out of the park, and documentary footage appeared on the Internet shortly afterwards.
The most inveterate group of protesters took refuge near the kitchen in their camp, which lay near the center of the park.
Some set up a roadblock, and the police began their methodical arrests.
About ten people in the center of the camp were chained to each other.
And two people were tied to a tree, Mr. Kelly said.
Members of the emergency services were called in to cut the locks.
There were no arrests in the park until 3:30 a.m., Mr. Kelly said.
The entire operation was completed about 75 minutes later, police said.
Mr Browne said about 142 people had been detained in the park.
Most of the arrests were due to "organizing riots and resisting arrest," he explained.
The highest-ranking police officer at the scene was Joseph J. Esposito, commander of the police department, the highest-ranking uniformed officer in the department.
Phil T. Pulaski, the department's chief of detectives, was also personally involved in the operation.
Mr. Kelly was present, but "he was not involved in the management of the operation," Mr. Browne said.
A second group of officers waited along the east side of Broadway, between Liberty Street and Cedar Street, in case they needed to be called.
Blocks were erected on Cortlandt Street, a block north of the park, and on Pine Street, a block south of the park.
From these places, the police then developed a protective belt even further away from Zuccotti Park.
At one point, police officers were seen, many of whom were equipped with shields, pushing people further beyond that border.
There were about 28 people on the northern border.
The wildest events of the night took place south of the park.
About five o'clock in the morning, one protester south of Pine Street was seen jumping onto the hood of a police car, and several others spewing air from the police van's tires.
At one point, a piece of plywood flew out of the crowd.
At the end of the operation, one police officer and one protester were hospitalized.
Union of Auxiliary Workers will sue the city for dismissal
Unions representing hundreds of school support workers who lost their jobs last month are planning to sue the city on Wednesday, saying layoffs were unnecessary and discriminatory because of the disproportionate impact on schools attended by poor students.
The litigation is probably the last option left to the District Council 37 trade unions in their efforts to overturn the dismissal decision.
On October 7, six hundred and seventy-two school assistants, parent coordinators and other employees who were among the city's worst paid employees lost their jobs. Their dismissal was described by leading union members as retaliation for the city's failure last spring to allow them access to a health care fund managed by labor detachments, with the help of which the city wanted to fund the budget.
City officials categorically rejected the accusation.
At a City Council meeting last month, Education Secretary Dennis M. Walcott said the layoffs were part of a budget approved in June.
One of the board members immediately countered that the budget did not specifically mention the dismissal of auxiliaries.
District Council 37 officials said they had already filled out the necessary documents and warned the Department of Education that they would sue him. On Wednesday, they will convene a press conference, where they will formally announce the lawsuit to the Supreme State Court in Manhattan.
The defendants in the trial will be Mr. Walcott and the Department of Education, while the plaintiffs will be eight dismissed workers, all of whom are African-American or Hispanic, as well as most of the other assistants who lost their jobs.
Elizabeth Thomas, a spokeswoman for the city's legal department, said the city had not yet seen the lawsuit and would not comment on the individual charges.
According to a complaint filed with the New York Times, unions focused on the number of layoffs in poor parts of the city to bolster their claims of unfair treatment, arguing that poor schools have lost more assistants because they have long been denied sufficient funding.
They point out that while there were no layoffs at all in the Staten Island school district and at least a minimum in the Upper East Side, there were 17 school assistants in Brooklyn, District 23 in Brownsville, and 46 in South Bronx, District 8 and District 9.
He recalls that five out of eight assistants lost their jobs at Public School 36 in Harlem, even though it is a school where 68 percent of students live in poverty. The lawsuit says: "It's not a neighborhood full of moveable parents who can get funds to cover the budget deficit."
Public School 36’s budget was cut by 3.26 percent this year, and the school also lost money when the city changed the way bonus funds were calculated for each enrolled poor student.
The unions say, among other things, that high school principals may have been confused by the way in which a document approving the dismissal of parental coordinators was written.
In the document, the word "excess" was used to describe the action, i.e. to cancel the position, although this word is used much more often to describe the transfer of a teacher from the school payroll to the database of available workers whose wages are paid by the central authority.
"Sixty-six parent coordinators have been dismissed," the complaint said, "and not just moved to a database in a position of available staff."
The mission is over, Congress is ready to accept an agreement on the situation in Libya
Finally, it seems that Republicans and Democrats in Congress agree on something regarding the uprising in Libya.
But before that happened, the revolution had to succeed, long-ruling dictator Muammar Gaddafi had to be captured and killed, and the participation of United States troops ended.
On Tuesday, the Senate Foreign Relations Committee will decide on a statement supported by President John Kerry (Mass.) along with Senators John McCain (Ariz.) and Joseph I. Lieberman (Conn.), in which it should congratulate Libyans on their successful uprising and thank U.S. troops for their "courage".
"With this statement, we want to acknowledge the courage of the people of Libya who have begun to rebuild their country," Kerry said.
"Both sides of the political spectrum would like to express their support for their democratic efforts."
These sentences may seem innocent, but no debate on Libya has been easy so far.
Over the summer, lawmakers from both sides have been arguing with each other and the White House about the wording of a series of statements to approve or reject the United States’ military role in NATO’s mission in Libya.
In June, Kerry and McCain introduced a resolution authorizing the limited use of U.S. military forces in Libya.
The motion was rejected in the House because of differences of opinion between the two political parties, so it was never even voted on in the Senate.
However, on the same day that the motion was rejected in the House, the chamber also rejected a measure that would have stopped funding US operations in Libya.
The U.S. mission in Libya was literally in legislative limbo — Congress criticized President Obama’s handling of the mission, but it apparently didn’t irritate members enough to stop supporting him.
In the end, the Congress’s hesitancy was preceded by other events.
The rebels captured Tripoli in August and Gaddafi was killed on 20 October.
The NATO mission officially ended on October 31.
Now the Senate may be ready to act.
In its statement, the Commission on International Relations "congratulates the people of Libya for their immense courage and admirable tenacity in their efforts to liberate their people" and "praise the men and women of the United States armed forces and their allies who have engaged in an operation to protect the Libyan population for their extraordinary bravery and professionalism."
The statement also “confirms the national interest of the United States in a successful and irreversible transition to democracy in Libya.”
Will the new proposal receive the full support of the Commission on Foreign Affairs, or will the legislators again be split into two halves, as was the case with the approval of the June proposal?
The latest version was opposed by Senator Richard G. Lugar (Ind.), the main representative of the Republican Party in the commission.
Lugar’s spokesman said on Monday that he had not yet seen the final version of the new proposal.
The House will vote this week on an amendment to the Constitution that would require a balanced budget, which should be the highest legislative priority of almost all Republicans and Democrats in Congress.
This measure, championed by Bob Goodlatt (Va.), will be the first amendment to the Constitution relating to a budget or other topic to be voted on by the entire House or Senate.
So far, despite considerable efforts, the other legislators have not managed to push their proposals to the vote.
Goodlatt’s proposal is just one of 68 amendments to the constitution that were introduced in Congress and touched on a wide range of different topics.
Some of them were the same - the same proposal presented to the House and Senate - and others are only minor changes of others.
Only in the House can you find at least 15 versions of the balanced budget amendment and another handful that would like to "regulate federal spending".
Some of the proposals are identical, but their proponents - especially novice Republicans who want to improve their reputations - can boast of their "authorship".
The budget regulation bill, which was approved in August, required both the House and Senate to vote on the balanced budget amendment.
In March, 58 senators voted in favor of a non-binding statement to support the creation of such an amendment.
In addition to the budget, several members want to discuss limits on the number of times members of Congress can serve, while José E. Serrano (N.Y.) wants to increase the number of times a president can serve.
Representative Jesse L. Jackson Jr. (Ill.) offered a range of additions that would, among other things, guarantee the right to quality education and medical care.
A permanent proposal remains an amendment banning same-sex marriage and an amendment banning the burning of the national flag.
Some lawmakers also want to allow federal laws to be repealed if two-thirds of states oppose them.
Although members of Congress seem to be very active in proposing various amendments, they do not significantly deviate from the average in comparison with previous years.
In the 111th Congress, 77 amendments were proposed, while in the 100th Congress there were 66.
Their activity even pales in comparison to the early 1990s, when, according to the statistics of the Senate Library, members offered more than 150 additions every two years.
However, they were not much more successful than the current politicians.
The last amendment, the 27th Amendment, was ratified in 1992, but was actually proposed by Congress in 1789.
