Troops meet with compassion rather than respect
The event was a Wall Street gala that brought in millions of dollars for war veterans in New York who don’t have a roof over their heads.
Kid Rock sang a ballad about helplessness, frustration and loss.
Hundreds of soldiers, sailors, airmen and marines gathered around him.
The solemnly dressed crowd rose and clapped enthusiastically.
"Both men and women serving in the military were considered heroes," said David Saltzman, who hosted the spring benefit.
In addition to Admiral Mike Mullen, who saw the role of military units somewhat differently, the chairman of the chiefs of staff took part in the gala evening.
"They were all presented as orphans," the officer wrote in an email.
I'm sure the organizers meant well.
I know you did.
But what I saw wasn't respect, it was regret.
Such completely opposite impressions only illustrate the difficult relationship between the army and the often measured, sometimes glorifying American public.
The army is full of praise for its victims.
But this praise costs something, the soldiers say.
The public is increasingly behaving as if the individual in uniform is regretting it.
"We are not victims at all," said Brigadier General Sean B. MacFarland, who commanded troops in Iraq and will soon leave Afghanistan.
"But it seems that the only way some people can support us is to put us in the role of unhappy souls."
This topic is very sensitive for military commanders who do not want to look ungrateful or spoil their relations with the public they serve.
They also realize that the anger that troops returning from Vietnam once had to face was far worse.
As a result, most words about regret are spoken quietly and privately among war veterans.
When the two sons of retired Colonel Mark Cancian returned from combat where they had served as Marines, their father warned them that outsiders would look at their service from two angles.
From the point of view of some, he will feel respect and amazement, because they defeated the enemy rebels and visited exotic places.
But others will wonder if "an evil, violent veteran is hiding beneath the surface," said Cancian, who took part in the fighting in Iraq and returned to Washington to take a seat in the government.
He claimed that when he was looking for a job, some of the people who interviewed him quietly suggested that he could resist the stress of working in Washington so soon after he returned from the fight.
"When you talk about your ministry, you have to count on negative reactions," Cancian told his sons.
The military’s concerns stem in part from America’s indifference to war.
Achievements on the battlefield are rarely recognized in a country that has little awareness of its own military and has little self-interest in the wars in Iraq and Afghanistan.
“As a nation, we no longer value military heroism as was common during World War II,” said Lt. Gen. David Barno, who commanded U.S. forces in Afghanistan.
Instead, recognition from politicians and the public focuses mainly on the suffering of men in arms.
Soldiers are rewarded for the number of actions they have suffered, the number of friends they have lost, or the extent of their injuries.
The military is facing increasing pressure to take a hard line against rape.
This week, it will decide whether to launch a trial of 28 women and men against the military over alleged inaction in the case of rape.
If not, hundreds of other plaintiffs are ready to sue.
Elizabeth Lyman, a first-class soldier, was 25 years old on the night she was allegedly raped by her army colleague and was 11 weeks pregnant.
It happened in October 2008 and she was heading to the barracks at Miramar Air Force Base north of San Diego. After dinner with a friend, she came across her male colleague carrying a box of 12 beers.
He asked her if he could join her for a drink in her room.
"There was a warning light in my head," Lyman said.
But the native Texasan completely ignored her objections.
I thought, no, he's 19.
"He's from Texas," she said.
"I wish I'd listened to my instincts."
She claims that just minutes after they entered her room, a man walked over to her, threw her on the bed and raped her.
This week, November 18, Lyman and 27 other current or former members of the military will be awaiting a verdict at a hearing that could have a historic impact. This will take place in Arlington, Virginia, and it will be about whether the charges against former Secretary of Defense Robert Gates and his predecessor, Donald Rumsfeld, will be brought before the court.
The indictment alleges that Gates and Rumsfeld failed to combat the spread of rape in the military, which is contrary to the constitutional rights of soldiers.
The indictment was filed in February by Washington lawyer Susan Burke, and the plaintiffs had 17 members at the time. However, over the following months, their number grew to 28-25 women and three men, all of whom claim to have been raped or otherwise sexually assaulted by their colleagues in the military, and that the military, after reporting these abductions, has failed in any way to prosecute, punish, and prosecute.
Burke says she’s going after the highest-ranking military commanders because the problem starts with them.
“The military is a directive system,” he says.
"Who are the people who are in a position to prevent efforts to impose measures against such acts?
Burke says she has contacted at least 400 other survivors since February, many of whom could become part of other lawsuits filed in the future.
Her strategy: Rather than putting all the charges in this case - putting all the eggs in one basket, as she says herself - she will file lawsuits in multiple different cases, if necessary, to keep the pressure on.
The Defense Department's defense team is led by U.S. Attorney Neil MacBride, who, along with his associates, filed a motion to dismiss the case.
The court documents obtained by Newsweek detail the defense’s strategy — essentially that current or former soldiers can’t sue the military for injuries they suffered as members of the armed forces.
According to a 1950 Supreme Court order known as the Feres Doctrine, the federal government is not responsible for injuries sustained by soldiers in active service.
"The alleged injuries relate to the defendants' military service," the document said.
The Department of Defense declined to comment on the matter.
But things have changed since the 1950s.
Although women are still not officially allowed to serve in combat, it is only a matter of word-of-mouth: in modern wars it is difficult to find a clearly defined front line.
In the wars in Iraq and Afghanistan, teams of female soldiers played an increasingly prominent role, especially in the area of communication with civilian women in the war zone.
The result: 150 female soldiers died between these wars – two-thirds of them directly in combat.
It’s time to modernize the military, Burke explains.
She's not alone in her fight, and three other lawyers are handling the case.
At Yale Law School, visitors to a veteran legal services seminar are preparing a lawsuit against four major military academies for allegedly developing an atmosphere conducive to hatred of women.
Independently, the non-profit organization of U.S. Vietnamese veterans is gathering evidence for its lawsuit aimed at the military. This lawsuit focuses on the diagnosis of "personality disorder" that was allegedly found in rape victims in order for the army to have an excuse to release them - according to activists such as Anu Bha's fighting groups.
In December, her group filed a lawsuit against the state-run organization for dealing with veterans, accusing them of discriminatory practices that should have occurred when processing requests for help from people who claimed to have been sexually assaulted in the service.
In Congress, nine separate proposals were put forward by a group of senators and MPs from both political parties, proposing a range of corrective measures.
According to the Office for the Prevention and Resolution of Sexual Violence of the Department of Defense, 3,158 sexual assaults were reported in 2010.
However, this type of attack remains unreported in most cases, and according to the Pentagon’s own estimates, this number corresponds to about 13.5 percent of the estimated 19,000 incidents that occurred in a given year.
In a report issued in March, the level of prosecution of suspects is also discussed: In 2010, 20 percent of cases reported in the military were brought to court - half of the civilian justice system.
Prosecutors in the case of Deputy Burke describe the attacks only as the first of a series of traumas.
