The Walls Have Eyes: How Scientists Examine You on Facebook
Before Anders Behring Breivik became the new face of right-wing extremism in Europe, he was just another young man to present his anti-immigrant views online.
On Monday, Braivik, who confessed to the July killing rampage that left 77 dead in Norway, attended his first public court hearing.
Although Breivik could act alone, he was certainly not alone in cyberspace: during the preparation of the attack, he spent a lot of time at the computer, chatting with some of the millions of nationalists supporting right-wing groups on social media sites.
After the tragedy of this summer, scientists want to learn more about these people.
But how to find them?
Easy - just go to Facebook.
“We realized that finding them isn’t really that hard at all,” said Jamie Bartlett, lead author of a recent report by a British research team on European digital populism.
The stock of personal information on Facebook is so vast, Bartlett says, that it was enough for scientists to simply use the ad on the site to pinpoint the demographic they were looking for — something that marketers have been doing for years.
Bartlett’s team found half a million right-wing group fans across Europe, and they focused on them and sent them ads. However, instead of inviting them to a newly formed group or offering them some dietary products, they invited them to fill out a questionnaire, in which there were questions about their level of education, attitude to violence and optimism.
Through Facebook, Bartlett and his colleagues managed to get results from more than 10,000 fans of 14 different right-wing groups in 11 European countries – without ever having to leave the office.
"It's a whole new way of doing research," Bartlett notes.
Some of the results are not all that surprising: online supporters of right-wing groups are mostly young men who are being pushed by the rising rate of immigration.
But on the other hand, “those who combine their online activism with offline activism are more reasonable, more democratic, and less violent than those who remain constantly hidden behind a computer screen.”
The work of the DEMOS team is just one example of how Facebook is becoming a new tool in the hands of scientists.
Research teams, health scientists, and political researchers use this site to study everything from health issues to social trends hiding in status updates, wall posts, and "Like" buttons.
Facebook reports more than 800 million active users. Each of them daily on average provides three different data, which makes this social network literally an "information supernova", which is behind the development of many new research. The number of academic works in the name of which the word Facebook appears has increased compared to the situation five years ago to almost 800%.
For some scientists, the magic of Facebook is that it gives them the opportunity to study people without having to bother them somewhere on the street.
"It used to be that when you wanted to do a survey among people from the British National Party, it was very difficult to identify them."
“You’d have to get to a side they’d never let you in,” Bartlett says.
“Facebook is tearing it all down — you’re just going straight to them.”
Others argue that the site can offer a way to identify and avoid a social health problem.
In a recent study by Dr. Megan Moreno of the University of Wisconsin, the research team found that university students who discussed their drunken Facebook posts were much more at risk of the problem of alcoholism than students who kept quiet about the topic.
Moreno suggests that students’ peers monitor the site and come up with an offer to help a student who posts too many drunken statuses.
“The problem can’t be solved if you can’t diagnose it,” said Dimitri Christakis, co-author of the study and director of the Center for Children’s Health, Behavior and Development at the Children’s Research Institute in Seattle.
“We have found a way to identify vulnerable children that we would otherwise not have a chance to detect.”
Facebook itself constantly probes the data of its users.
The site’s information team produced statistics on the relationship between relationship status and Valentine’s Day, voter turnout in 2010 and the nation’s satisfaction rate (mainly using information they had access to – internet freedom advocates have long argued that the site should make its information treasure available to others as well).
But Facebook users know that the site is watching them whether they like it or not - in exchange for the opportunity to play Scrabble with a friend who is thousands of kilometers away, you need to provide the site with your personal information.
But what if Facebook users become part of research they don’t even know about?
Scientists have clearly defined rules on how to collect data off-line, but online data is accessible to everyone.
“I don’t think most users would have thought that scientists could look at their profiles,” says Neil Selwyn, a sociologist at the London Knowledge Lab, about a 2006 study he conducted using the public Facebook walls of his students.
"As far as they were concerned, they took it to mean that the information was only between them and their friends."
Then the question of methodology is also considered.
Even in off-line research, there is no guarantee that the subject is completely honest.
There is no way to verify on Facebook how much of the information on the profile and wall posts are true.
“What you say on Facebook and what you do outside of Facebook are two completely different things,” Selwyn explains.
That’s why Selwin, who has spent many years researching new technologies, thinks that pencil and notebook remain the best possible tool to use in research.
“When you go out into the real world and talk to real people, it’s something that can’t be replaced,” he says.
“Societal research should be about society and social activities — and a hell of a lot of social activities are still taking place off-line.”
