7 Lessons from a Lost Conversation with Steve Jobs in a Movie Heading to the Movies This Week
When Steve Jobs died on October 5th, people began to compare him to Henry Ford – and they elected him as his genius The Greatest Modern Inventor.
Jobs’ recently rediscovered interview, which was dusted off for a special movie heading to theaters this week, will reveal to all Apple fans that his creative mind had a perfect understanding of the business processes and workflows behind his products.
He was an amazing designer, a dreamer and a self-proclaimed member of the hippie movement, but also a pedantic organizer and a person who fits every detail into the smallest detail - he believed that many entrepreneurs suffer "from the idea that a really great idea is 90 percent of their work ... [but] between a great idea and an excellent product is still a long way to go."
In 1995, Bob Cringely worked on the TV show Triumph of Computer Fools, which discussed the dawn of personal computers. During the filming, a unique, more than an hour-long interview took place.
It’s been ten years since Jobs was forced to leave Apple, and he’s been busy with his new computer company, NeXT, and he’s been looking forward to seeing how the general public embraces the internet.
In the end, only a short portion of Cringely's entire interview was used on the TV show, and the original copies of the interview were said to have been lost in transit.
Shortly after Jobs' death, VHS copies were found in the director's garage.
It is this material, slightly edited, that forms the basis of the 68-minute film Steve Jobs: The Lost Interview, which is heading to selected cinemas this Wednesday and Thursday.
For someone who is notorious for his reluctance to provide longer interviews, Jobs here seems surprisingly excited to talk about his technology philosophy and business strategies.
He also appears to be a very thoughtful person.
Four times during the interview, there will be a longer pause between the question and the answer - 10 to 15 seconds of thinking, when it is seen how Jobs thinks over the answer perfectly to make it as concise and accurate as possible.
There are also moments when Jobs’ perfectionism comes to the surface, when he is impatient with Cringely’s questions and prompts him to get to more important problems and topics faster.
The interview was filmed before the Pixar, iPod or iPhone era, and it’s terrifyingly prophetic as Jobs evaluates what other companies are doing right and wrong while offering his own vision of the future in the field of computer technology.
It’s one thing to read the posthumous reviews of Jobs’ career, but there’s something raw and inspiring about Jobs, whom we see here as a eager dreamer in the heyday of his genius.
It has its own vision of what things could and should look like.
It was not long before he began to put his ideas into practice.
A quick summary of the seven scenes from The Lost Interview that is definitely worth noting:
How he learned to run a business:
"Over the years of business, I've always asked, 'Why are you doing this?' and the answer has always been, 'Well, that's just how you do it.'
No one knows why he does what he does, never thinks deeply about things related to business.
That's what I found out.
Jobs goes on to describe his efforts to simplify accounting at Apple.
He was completely confused by the way in which costs were recorded - they often began with the inscription "standard costs", he could only guess about their amount. At that moment he decided to go his own way - he developed an automatic tool that guaranteed that they could determine the business costs within a moment.
How he made a mockery of the Pope:
Jobs recalls the "Blue Box" he built with Steve Wozniak - a device that allowed people to effectively hack into the phone company and make free calls anywhere in the world.
There’s been a lot written about the device in the past, but Jobs’ enthusiasm for describing the Blue Box as an instrument of power is literally contagious.
He tells how he and Wozniak tested the devices using a pay phone and during the call, they were allowed to switch from one AT&T network to another, while using as many satellites as possible.
“We’ve been around the world like this at least a half-dozen times, so when we yelled into a pay phone, it came a minute later from the other phone at the door,” Jobs laughs.
“We were young and we found that we could build a thing ourselves that is capable of running billions of dollars’ worth of infrastructure around the world.”
The two of us made a tiny thing that could control a much bigger giant - it was an incredible experience and I don't think Apple would ever have come into being without it.
Jobs goes on to describe the joke that he and Wozniak almost finished. Through the Blue Box in the middle of the night, they called the Vatican and asked if they could talk to the Pope, posing as best they could as Henry Kissinger.
Gradually, more and more high-ranking members of the Catholic Church were summoned to speak with an American diplomat in the middle of the night, and only just before they woke up the Pope himself to the phone, did the pair laugh and lay down.
How he fell in love with technology (and phoned Bill Hewlett):
When he was 12 and looking for spare parts to build his own oscillator, he found Bill Hewlett's number in his phone book and called him.
Not long after their 20-minute conversation, Jobs had already secured a summer job at Hewlett-Packard.
"It was the only company I knew at the time, and it shaped my view of what a company is and how it should treat its employees."
Jobs later became one of HP’s employees who visited the company’s research labs in Palo Alto, where he saw “the first desktop computer ever made.”
It was as big as a suitcase, had a CRT monitor, and I instantly fell in love with it.
As a teenager, I went higher and higher at HP, hung around the computer, and started writing programs for it.
How to Invent Innovation:
In several places, Jobs talks during the interview about how he invents new products on the run.
Early in his career, when he set out to sell a few printed circuit boards, one customer asked him to put together a whole computer for him.
He had only 30 paid days, during which he had to invent, assemble and deliver the finished equipment.
Later, when he was at Apple, he recalled the problems they faced when developing a computer mouse:
“I remember we were fighting pretty wildly... screaming at me that it would take five years [to build a mouse that would cost $300] to get it to stop bothering me, and I went out and found myself a designer.”
Ninety days later, we were able to produce a perfectly reliable mouse for $15.
How big a company takes its breath away:
Long before leading Apple’s resurrection, Jobs had prudently predicted that many industry leaders in his vision would falter and lose market share.
“Let’s say you work for IBM or Xerox, so you make better copiers or printers, so what’s next?”
You have a monopoly on the market, so the company can no longer be more successful.
At that moment, sales and marketing are already in control, so companies are led by people who are in charge of just that, while people who are in charge of their own products are out of the decision-making process.
The technological genius that has led society to its unshakable position is now replaced by people who have no idea of good or bad products - skill and technical knowledge are essential.
This is exactly what happened at Xerox.
Xerox could literally own the entire computer industry.
It could have been ten times bigger than it is, it could have been Microsoft in the 1990s...
Instead of winning, they lost.
How to use innovation as an art form:
“Between a great idea and a great product, there is still a long way to go and a lot of work... and as that great idea evolves, so does it change and grow.”
You will learn a lot about him during that time.
You have to make a whole series of compromises - you don't force certain things just by electrons, glass, robots or factories.
You have to keep 5,000 things in mind all the time - different concepts - and put them together...
In the end, it depends on taste – you try to think about the best things that humanity has ever created, and in some way you try to project them into what you yourself are doing.
Picasso said that good artists copy, but the best artists steal.
I've never been ashamed of stealing the best ideas.
Macintosh was so amazing and successful because the people who worked at it were excellent musicians, poets, artists, zoologists, historians, and coincidentally also the best computer experts in the world.
Without computers and new technologies, they could do amazing things in completely different industries.
Scalia and Thomas had dinner with opponents of the health care law while their case was being investigated by a court.
On the day the Supreme Court sat behind closed doors to discuss the politically controversial question of whether to accept an objection to President Obama’s healthcare bill, two of his judges, Antonin Scalia and Clarence Thomas, attended a dinner ceremony sponsored by a law firm that will be attending the hearings in court.
