However, if this were not the case, their conduct would definitely fall under the principle of C4, which states that "the judge may participate in events that are being organized by related and other organizations in order to raise funds, but the judge must not be a speaker, an honorary guest, nor be listed on the program of the event."
Yet Scalia’s and Thomas’s relationship with the two law firms involved in the case, as well as the companies with huge financial interests in the case, was rich enough to alarm activists calling for ethics in the government.
