How to Recognize a Lie
A cursory glance at recent newspaper headlines suggests how serious and pervasive lies and deceptions are in everyday life.
Republican presidential candidate Herman Cain is busy with allegations that he sexually harassed several women — both sides claiming the other is lying.
Administrators at Penn State University were accused of perjury when they tried to hide records of a retired football coach sexually assaulting a boy.
Last week, French President Nicolas Sarkozy was caught telling US President Barack Obama with a microphone that Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu is a liar.
The lie has destroyed entire careers and undermined the stability of many countries.
New York congressman and Internet exhibitionist Anthony Weiner made a fool of himself when he published information that was immediately refuted by indisputable evidence.
Former presidential candidate John Edwards has been accused of using campaign funds to try to keep his marriage a secret.
And no one will ever forget the media circus that rallied around Bill Clinton when he lied during his second term in office about his sexual relationship with Monica Lewinsky.
There are stories of cheating at school and at university.
There are cases where teachers themselves give their students test answers just to make themselves look good in their assessments.
Mentors who should teach the opposite are sending a message that lying and cheating is acceptable.
How many frauds do we face?
Studies show that in a single day you lie somewhere between 10 and 200 cases.
Let us suppose that many of them are merciful lies.
Another study showed that strangers lied three times during the first ten minutes of the first meeting in their lives.
Defining lies, or “recognizing lies,” is a necessary skill that everyone should acquire, whether for personal or professional reasons.
However, it is not a social game that is similar to, say, Sharada, when a person shouts: "I have you." Recognition of deception is a serious branch of science working with scientific data collected over the past six decades at prestigious universities during detailed research projects, especially in the field of psychology and philosophy.
One of the results of the research is that most of the old myths about lies have been refuted.
The liars look you in the eye.
It's not like they're squirming, stuttering, blushing, or shivering.
But do not assume that it is somehow difficult to spot and expose the liars.
A trained identifier of a lie can reveal the truth from a sentence structure, small facial expressions, the way questions are created and their timing.
I have spent several years gathering scientific knowledge from a large and developing industry concerning the recognition of lies, and it is clear that the detection of deception is a modern skill that can be easily learned and can be of great help in today's complex world - especially if your job responsibilities include hiring, arranging interviews, negotiating or guiding people.
Good liars can read well in others, let them relax in vigilance, direct their emotions, and intuitively realize how the other side accepts them.
We know from research that extroverts lie more often than introverts, that men tell more “self-centered” lies, while women tell more lies “focused on others” – mostly to protect one’s feelings – that married people lie less often to their partners than single people (but the lies they say are usually “indecent.”
We also know that if you are perceived as a sinner, others feel less guilty when they lie to you.
How do you know if someone is lying?
First, observe the normal behavior of the subject.
This is called “initial observation.”
Thanks to him, he will have a later finding with what to compare.
Notice the posture of the subject, his laughter, work with the voice.
You should know if someone is routinely tapping their feet all the time so that you don’t unjustifiably accuse them of lying just because they start tapping their feet in the middle of a meeting.
Then try to identify clusters of false verbal and nonverbal behavior.
However, take it only as a warning signal, not as evidence of a lie.
People who tell a lie may stop moving the upper half of their body when trying to remember their made-up story, they may tip their shoes toward the door, bend to the exit, significantly change their posture, or show "relief after the conversation" - excessive relief breathing and changing position when it is difficult to confess to them.
Interviewers often give a false signal that the interview is over, just to see what the relief will look like after it is over.
Notice also the language of the subject.
There is a famous story about how Scott Peterson once argued and used the past tense when he claimed his murdered wife was alive, sparking a nationwide search for her body.
Deceptive individuals may also express themselves in a measured way: "I had no sexual relationship with this lady... Miss Lewinsky" or repeat the difficult question.
The most common verbal signs are very slight.
Someone can use a lot of "softening language" when answering the difficult question: "Well... to tell the truth... from what I know... to the best of my knowledge."
In such a response, we do not learn too many facts, and often this is another warning signal.
There is no magic that can reveal every lie, but it is possible to acquire skills that can be used to investigate a lie.
By using these skills, a person will have a greater chance of not running into a liar and fraudster in his personal and professional life.
