A few days after the Obama administration threatened to delay the approval of a planned oil pipeline from Canada to the Gulf of Mexico — infuriating trade unions but reassuring environmentalists — the pipeline company announced it was willing to redirect the project to get things moving again.
TransCanada announced on Monday evening that it will move the planned pipeline route from the environmentally sensitive Sandhills area of Nebraska, and is confident that the project will be approved anyway.
The company announced this decision at a press conference at the headquarters of the Nebraska government.
TransCanada’s Alex Pourbax says the company is confident that the pipeline will eventually be approved, even though it will take a different route.
The announcement came after the Foreign Office announced last week that it was postponing a decision on federal approval of the project, from which it would not conduct a study of possible replacement routes that would avoid the Sandhills area in Nebraska and the aquifer Ogallala, a vast underground water reservoir.
"This is a real step forward," Rep. Lee Terry of Nebraska told Fox News.
A new environmental review ordered by the foreign ministry would likely postpone any decision until 2013, a year after next year’s elections, but authorities have refused to allow politics to play a role in the decision.
