Climate change has slowed the economy
During the first year of the government of Maria L<0xC3><0xB3>pez Valdez, unemployment and unreliability rose in Sinaloa, foreign investment fell, and with it the economy.
The year 2011 will go down in Sinaloa's economic history. This is the first year of the government of Mario L<0xC3><0xB3>pez Valdez, which calls itself the Government of Change. This government has brought with it great expectations in terms of economic progress, however, due to adverse climatic conditions at the beginning of the year, no growth has been recorded and even the main indicators of economic development have declined.
Low February temperatures have caused millions of losses in the field of agriculture, reduced the possibilities of growth of the state economy, they are responsible for a decrease in economic activity by 3.6% in the first semester of this year. In the field of agriculture, there was a historical decrease of 31.16%, which disrupted the dynamics of other economic sectors.
According to the report on the damage caused, published by the Mexican Council for Sustainable Rural Development, damage was recorded on 582,835 hectares of arable land, of which 78.03% was completely destroyed, and partial damage was found on the remaining 21.07%. Among the main destroyed crops are vegetables, corn and games.
The decline in economic activity until November caused a constant increase in unemployment in the state of unemployment of about 9 percent. According to the National Institute of Statistics and Geography, the unemployment rate in the state also recorded an increased increase during the first three quarters. From January to March, 55,053 people were unemployed in the state of Sinaloa, which represents an unemployment rate of 4.53% of the economically active population. In the second quarter, the unemployment rate was 5 percent of the economically active population.
Less liquidity
