Miguel Loredo L<0xC3><0xB3>pez, president of the National Chamber of Transformative Industries, said that in 2011 there was a lack of alignment of the will of individual sectors, including the state government itself.
"The economic development in Sinaloa has been really small this year. We have to work hard to recover the land we lost this year. In 2012, we have to redouble our efforts, there was no harmonisation of the efforts of all of us, and especially the correct and synchronized functioning of this new government. Hopefully next year will be much better," he said.
Slowness of the economy
Loredo L<0xC3><0xB3>pez said that events such as the frost at the beginning of the year stopped the state economy and limited its development and growth.
"The weak economic movement was caused by a number of events, including frost. One of the main consequences was the slowdown of the economy, which did not recover quickly enough to restore the dynamism that would allow to achieve an acceptable level of movement of processes, products and services. Therefore, at the end of the year, we found ourselves deep below the expected"
Re-defining the mission
According to Teodoro Salazar Uriarte, president of the Mexican Confederation of Employers in Sinaloa, the state needs to be pushed for more dynamic productive activities.
"Generally speaking, we are observing that work is being done. We believe that a long-term plan needs to be prepared in which the goals and economic direction of the state are redefined, because it is important to mobilize all the potential of material and human resources that Sinaloa has," he said.
