Court Approves ‘End of Analog Broadcasting’ in Mexico in 2015
Replacing analog signals with digital signals is one of the most important changes the world has experienced in recent years.
The Supreme State Court (SCJN) has rejected a constitutional lawsuit filed by the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies against the presidential decree, which wants to speed up the so-called "shutdown of analog signals" and implement it in 2015 instead of 2021. It noted that the necessary eight votes were not found to invalidate it.
A minority of four ministers, including the president of the court, Juan Silva Mez, believed that President Felipe Calder<0xC3><0xB3>n had not exceeded his authority when he issued a decree setting out the individual steps that would lead to the transition to terrestrial digital television.
As a result, the action brought by the Senate was dismissed, because a qualified majority of eight votes needed to enable the court to rule on the constitutionality or unconstitutionality of the said decree, which thus remains valid, was not achieved.
The draft judgment drafted by Minister Olga Sánchez Cordero proposes the possibility of declaring the decree unconstitutional, since the regulation of all issues related to radio and television is a matter that is reserved by law to the Federal Telecommunications Commission (Cofetel). This violates the principles of hierarchical subordination and exceptions to the law.
Only Zald<0xC3><0xAD>var, Jorge Mario Pardo, Margarita Luna and Sánchez Cordero voted for the project.
With this argument, both the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies supported the constitutional dispute in an attempt to combat the decree. Minister Sánchez Cordero accepted the demands and suspended the application of the decree and all the actions described in it, leading to the transition to digitalization.
The meeting of ministers also decided to reject the action brought by the Chamber of Deputies without entering into a discussion on the proposal, which is also in charge of Minister Sánchez Cordero.
In his speech, the Prime Minister stated that he did not identify with the arguments of the proposal in the sense that the federal executive could not structure through general standards measures to prepare the public administration.
"I don't think that even if she did, it would affect the autonomy of the regulator," and he recalled that public policy planning in strategic areas such as the telecommunications sector belongs to the federal executive, which has a constitutional mandate to determine the direction of the state.
The replacement of analog signals with digital signals is one of the biggest changes the world has experienced in recent years. It is related to better use of the radio-electric spectrum, better signal quality and more channels.
He believes that postponing change would mean postponing the benefits of digitalisation, which requires decisions in the public interest, because digitalisation does not only have a technical dimension, but also "affects economic, social, political and national security issues".
As he stressed, these issues "require the operation of the entire established system, in accordance with the principle of the economic direction of the state. It includes a whole range of competences that the Constitution entrusts to the state government."
He recalled that a number of countries around the world have already completed the transition to the digital system and have done so through their governments, despite having highly specialized technical bodies at their disposal.
He said that it was not possible for the government, by issuing a dissenting decree that to some extent interfered with the powers of Congress, to introduce compliance with laws prepared by the legislature into the area of administration.
