Quintet included the country in its tour to celebrate 20 years of existence
“A trip to Costa Rica is a dream that becomes a reality”
In an exclusive interview with Viva, Pearl Jam bassist Jeff Ament said the band is ready to offer one of the best shows at the National Stadium next Sunday.
We have been waiting for more than 20 years, but the group itself assures that the opportunity to play in Costa Rica is a dream come true for them.
So said bassist and founding member Jeff Ament, who spoke exclusively with Viva last week from Brazil.
The group is located on the South American continent as part of a tour to celebrate 20 years of existence and will be at a unique stop in Central America on Sunday the 20th.
On this day they will perform at 19:30 at the National Stadium together with the angel band The X and the national musicians from Las Robertas.
This is an excerpt from an interview, the full transcript of which can be found on La Naci<0xC3><0xB3>n's website.
For your Costa Rican fans, this is a dream come true. Pearl Jam will play in Costa Rica. Do you realize what your fans are experiencing?
A trip to Costa Rica is also a dream that becomes a reality.
In South and Central America, we have barely made it to the second time and the experience so far has been great.
I've only been to Costa Rica once, on vacation, it's a beautiful country, and I believe we'll be able to stay here for a few days.
So we are very happy to bring you our music.
I ask, because they literally love the band here, the fans are experiencing these days of preparation very intensely.
What do you say to your most ardent supporters?
Thank you for standing with us for so many years.
It took us almost 21 years to get to Costa Rica. Thank you for waiting so long and we are sorry that it took us so long.
Some people refer to the show as the biggest show of the year.
Does that put more pressure on you?
Some of the biggest shows we’ve done in the last 21 years have come out in a matter of weeks.
We did some great shows in S<0xC3><0xA3>o Paulo and we hope that this will get us in shape for a concert in Costa Rica.
We are really looking forward to this concert.
We love this country, we love surfing, we love the jungle. For both activities, Costa Rica is the best country in the world.
How did you get to know Costa Rica and its surf-friendly waves?
We have a lot of surfer friends and I have a good friend who lives in Tamarindo. The waves here are incredible.
My friends go surfing in Costa Rica or Nicaragua or Mexico. These are the best places to surf. And so we learned about Costa Rica, through people who love surfing.
If we look at your tour, you have prepared a huge show with many songs.
What did you plan for your presentation in Costa Rica?
Since we've never played here, there's no limit to what we can't do.
We will try to perform the best show with a variety of songs. We will try to play a few songs from each album and introduce our fans to a good and diverse repertoire.
You never repeat the repertoire.
Why? Why?
I think it’s partly because we have nine albums and we can play more than 120 songs and everyone likes different songs, so it’s hard to choose what songs we’re going to play every night.
When we have two or three songs in our repertoire that we haven’t played for a long time, we focus on them and we’re also surprised because we remember why we liked them so much and that we may have forgotten about it.
So the show is more interesting for us, and that's why I think it's more interesting for people.
This tour celebrates 20 years of artistic career.
Looking back, is it hard to believe everything you’ve done?
Yes, I'm sure.
First of all, I don't think any of us could have imagined being in one big rock band and staying in one for more than 20 years. That sounds like a dream.
We are aware of how much has been given to us and we are impressed that we can continue to play together.
We love each other and we love making music.
We're lucky to be able to see the places we've always wanted.
We couldn't have done better.
What did it mean to you that you were a significant part of the creation of the grunge genre?
It has always been an honor for us to be a part of this group in which the greats themselves are represented.
The people of Soundgarden, Mudhoney and Alice in Chains are our friends.
It is surprising when the movement arises from a group of friends, it does not happen very often.
From time to time, a group arises in a city, but it is much less common for five to ten groups to emerge from one city at a time.
We are proud and honored to be part of the Seattle group.
Sometimes we play with some of them.
Last year we were at the festival with Alice in Chains and we were in Canada with Mudhoney, we saw Soundgarden on tour. We are lucky that they are all our friends and we are honored to be part of this movement that originated in Seattle.
It is also very unusual for a group like yours to stay together and still have the same members after all these years.
Yes, the four of us have been together for 21 years and Matt (Cameron) joined us 13 years ago, which in itself is a much longer time than the usual duration of the group.
I think, firstly, we are all lucky that we are still in this world, and secondly, the fact that we are constantly interested in each other plays a role.
We are all close friends and thanks to this we have been able to open up musical paths that leave everyone enough freedom to experiment on their own.
We trust each other, we appreciate each other’s music and I don’t think it could have been better.
Your relationship to the word fame was not easy. However, thanks to your success, you can do what you like.
How do you find balance?
As we grew, it became increasingly easy to find balance.
We try not to tour too much, because it’s very easy to fall into this trap of crowds and people who love our music.
When you realize that people came for the music, you remind yourself that you have to respect the music and what you gave it. You must not get carried away by being famous, rock stars. This has never really interested any of us.
What do you think of Mother Love Bone?
I think we wrote great songs, and it was something spectacular in the beginning.
As a band, we existed for three years and never released an album until after Andy (Andrew Woods) died.
It was very frustrating because it took so long. The most important thing is that even today we are friends with Bruce (Fairweather) and Greg (Gilmore), who started in the band with us. When I listen to a song or look at photos, I remember Andy, how incredible he was, how happy I was with him, and how happy I was with him.
She was an incredible person and we miss her very much.
The national band Las Robertas will be commissioned to start the show in Costa Rica.
Is it true that you know their work, especially Eddie Vedder, and that that's why you chose them as your forerunners?
Yes, the production sent us videos with several designs and we liked this group the most. Therefore, we are curious what Las Robertas will offer live and they must be very entertaining.
Why do you always change the words Yellow Ledbetter live?
That's a question for Ed (Eddie Vedder), so I don't know.
He sings it, and I think he's adding the first thing that comes to his mind.
Who influences you as a bass player?
A lot of people.
My first thoughts are Geezer Butler, John Entwistle, C. J. Ramone, John Doe, Paul McCartney, Chuck Dukowski...
There are so many that I could talk all night about the bass players I like.
How did Pearl Jam manage to keep grunge, even though it is no longer in vogue?
I think we've all always felt a little bit detached from the word grunge.
When I say grunge, I think of the bands that I mentioned like Mudhoney, Soundgarden, Nirvana and all the other bands that came out at the same time, and if music like that is still relevant today, it's something great because it's music that's worth listening to, and bands like Mudhoney are playing better music today than ever before.
In the beginning, your music had a slightly gloomy character and now it is more positive.
What is behind this change?
That’s interesting because I feel like there’s a couple of songs in the new album that are a little bit lighter, but there’s also songs like The End or Juste Breathe that are considered very dark, although they may sound positive.
For both of them, when Ed played them for me, I cried, and they're songs that are deeply dark.
I think that when you grow up and you have some trauma in your life, you lose someone in your family or a friend, these things start to affect your art and your music, and these two songs for me represent just that.
I also think you can be a happy person and still make gloomy music.
