Fujimori Hospitalized Again for Medical Tests
Former President Alberto Fujimori has been hospitalized in a public hospital where he will be tested for muscle loss in the lower extremities, his doctor said.
Fujimori, 72, who is serving a 25-year sentence for human rights violations committed by his government (1990-2000), suffers from several illnesses, including tongue cancer, which he underwent four surgeries for and is already under the control of doctors.
Alejandro Aguinaga, a member of parliament who is his personal physician, told Canal N television that Fujimori would undergo tests at the National Institute of Neoplastic Diseases within three days to find out why he was in pain and why he was losing strength in his lower limbs.
Aguinaga said he believed Fujimori could be pardoned for humanitarian reasons, but the former president himself did not want the pardon because he felt innocent.
He was operated on four times for tongue cancer, lost 18 kilograms, and other ailments such as severe erosive gastritis, pancreatic cysts, kidney stones, high pressure and circulatory problems in the legs, the doctor said.
Fujimori has been serving his sentence since September 2007 at the National Directorate of Special Police Operations.
In April 2009, he was sentenced to 25 years in prison for the death of 25 people killed by a murderous squadron of troops operating illegally in the first years of his reign.
