Mexican Health Insurance Institute Launches Research Into Gene That Causes Obesity
The Institute of Health Insurance conducts research to discover the gene responsible for obesity in children and adolescents. The research is carried out with the support of experts from the IPN Institute
The Mexican Institute of Health Insurance (IMSS) announced that it is conducting research to detect the gene that causes obesity in children and young people. The research called "Genetics of obesity in children and adolescents" will allow to obtain results regarding overweight.
In a report, the head of the Biochemistry Research Medical Unit at the National Health Center Specialized Hospital of the 21st Century, Miguel Cruz L<0xC3><0xB3>pez, explained that a multidisciplinary team consisting of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social workers has been established.
This team relies on the support of specialists and postgraduate students from the National Institute of Public Health (INSP) and the Center for Research and Advanced Studies (Cinvestav) of the National Polytechnic Institute (IPN).
The general public, with or without a license, can also participate in the research. People can come to the participating sports centers of the IMSS in Valle de Mexico, where tests will be carried out every Saturday from 8 a.m. to 8 a.m.
He pointed out that the research started at the Cuauhtémoc Sports Centre (Mexico State) and since 8 October this activity has also been carried out at the Nezahualc<0xC3><0xB3>yolt Sports Centre (East of Mexico State).
As soon as the data is collected from 500 to 600 children, the study will continue at the Independencia Sports Center (south of the Federal District) and finally at the Morelos Sports Center (north of the Federal Center).
He explained that the aim of this research is to determine the components and importance of genetics in terms of the development of obesity, and to trace risk factors on Mexican children and young people, thereby preventing the development of chronic degenerative diseases.
On the occasion of International Diabetes Day, which is celebrated on November 14, he recalled that the goal is to collect data from three thousand children and young people between the ages of six and 14, with the consent and under the supervision of parents, for the application of specific nutritional questionnaires.
The questionnaire will also ask about the physical activity and family history of hereditary diseases in order to avoid risk factors that could cause diseases such as diabetes or kidney failure.
He specified that anthropometric measurements (weight, height, waist circumference) are carried out with all participants every Saturday, blood pressure is measured, glucose, triglycerides, cholesterol, insulin levels are determined and genes are examined (they try to identify genes that are involved in the development of childhood obesity).
Cruz L<0xC3><0xB3>pez said the research reflects health officials’ concerns about the alarming rise in child weight.
"Health surveys conducted between 1999 and 2006 showed that in just six years there was a 77% increase in obesity in boys and 47% in girls, and a dramatic increase in overweight," said the IMSS expert.
He said that one of the reasons for the search for indicators is the assumption that the population of the country differs from other populations by its genetic history.
He reported that the average Mexican has 65% Indian-American genetic equipment, 30% European and 5% African. This fact is reflected in the genes that are responsible for the development of diabetes and overweight.
He explained that, in general, the genetics of obesity is commonly explained as the inability to burn excess energy that we consume (calories) and which is stored in the form of fats.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit of the participants is that they get an overall assessment of the condition of the children, thus determining whether they show any known overweight or obesity.
He stated that even the presence of dark-colored wrinkles (acantosis) on the neck and forearms indicates the likelihood that the individual will suffer from metabolic problems and pre-diabetes conditions.
So far, the information is confidential, doctors pass it on in writing to parents and explain to them all the measurements and lifestyle changes they have to make to avoid their children from getting sick.
Cruz L<0xC3><0xB3>pez explained that there are three main components that cause overweight, obesity and other chronic diseases: a sedentary lifestyle that means a lack of daily physical activity, sitting in front of the TV all day and using vehicles instead of walking for short distances.
Excess weight is also caused by a large caloric intake, that is, a greater consumption of sweetened beverages, carbohydrates (tamales, bread, pizza, hamburgers, etc.) with a high content of fats and proteins, and the genetic load that is the subject of this research.
UNAM Asphalt won't have potholes
Rafael Herrera, a scientist at the UNAM Faculty of Chemistry, creates modified asphalts with polymers, creating a mixture that has better functionality, regardless of climatic conditions and temperature.
If paving was properly cared for, there would be no need to repair nearly 200,000 potholes after each rainy season in the Valle de Mexico Metropolitan Area, said Rafael Herrera Nájera, a scientist at the UNAM Faculty of Chemistry (FQ), who added that even if the construction and maintenance of asphalt pavements were possible, it would be appropriate to remove them.
In his lecture Technological Causation of Rifts, delivered as part of the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory under his leadership is developing modified asphalts with polymers, which should result in a mixture having similar characteristics as asphalt, but at the same time greater mechanical resistance, both at low and at high temperatures.
Herrera Nájera believes that this type of modified asphalt could be used in places with extremely warm climates, for example, in some cities in the north of the country. This would improve functionality and reduce the formation of potholes.
He explained that asphalt, the heaviest part of oil, is a grouping of hydrocarbon molecules, molecules with a large molecular weight called asphaltenes, and others with a low molecular weight called mortarenes. Together, they give asphalt a typical viscoelastic character.
The viscoelastic nature of asphalt lies in the fact that at high temperatures, about 180 degrees, it behaves like a liquid, at 120 degrees it has high viscosity and at 50 degrees it is almost in a solid state, while at low temperatures asphalt tends to break, he added.
This means that the resistance of asphalt in the streets is not uniform, but changes during the day according to meteorological conditions and temperature, said the expert in chemical engineering.
A scientist from the Faculty of Chemistry observed that most of the streets in Mexico City are covered with flexible paving, consisting of six layers of materials, the last three of which are mixed with asphalt.
Among the topmost layers there is an asphalt insert, formed by small pebbles poured into the asphalt and then compressed.
He stressed that every stone that forms the insert is covered with asphalt.
When passing cars or when creating pressure, it is thus possible for the forces in the pavement to decompose well.
If it was a modified asphalt, they would have decomposed even better, the chemical engineer believes.
He added that the last layer called the mantle, consisting of fine stones, i.e. sand also poured into the asphalt, would be placed on the asphalt insert.
Since this layer will come into contact with the rims of vehicles, it must have a greater mechanical strength than the asphalt insert and must ensure the friction of the road.
Since as part of the paving will be subjected to a large load, the shell must be of sufficient thickness and must be careful of the material from which it is made.
Climate, especially humidity and temperature changes, are also a very important factor to keep in mind. In particular, water has a great influence on the functionality of the asphalt insert.
Once the terrain is wet, the water spreads inward and is difficult to get out, this causes softening of all layers of the tiles and thus the formation of potholes.
He explained that during the creation of potholes, the film of the shell is first damaged and only then the asphalt insert is damaged. But the damage does not occur at one time, but it is a gradual process that should stop at the first signs with the help of appropriate maintenance programs.
As a member of the National System of Scientists, he also explained that the load of vehicles is another important factor in the formation of potholes, and therefore the thickness of each individual layer of tiles must correspond to the load of vehicles and must ensure that this load is not exceeded. Only in this way can we prevent the frequent occurrence of potholes.
Rafael Herrera pointed out that when it comes to asphalt, we still have a lot of work to do and research is at the beginning. It is worth mentioning, for example, asphalt emulsions, which are already available on the market in other countries and allow you to easily repair potholes without having to use high temperatures.
