Energy policy:
Facts must triumph over dogmas.
If there is a topic that cannot be grasped on the basis of short-term balance sheets or under emotions, then it is energy policy.
The availability and price of electricity have a direct impact on the purchasing power and competitiveness of enterprises.
It is natural that the election meeting should be an opportunity to think about such deposits and about the place that takes energy from the core.
The debate will be successful only if all the economic, social and environmental consequences of the proposed options are explored.
The French must base their position on objective facts and rational data.
There are 7 billion human beings on the planet so far, but demographic developments will trigger a doubling of electricity demand by 2050 if we do not want to deprive a significant part of the world’s population of an important part of life.
At the same time, the lack of fossil resources will have to be tackled in order to continue producing electricity, while not forgetting the necessary need to reduce greenhouse gas emissions in order to combat climate change, a subject that is currently disappearing from environmental debates.
The Fukushima accident does not affect any of these parameters.
And that is why Germany alone remains in its decision to refuse nuclear energy.
But this is not the case in Belgium, which submits its decision to find some other source capable of replacing itself, nor in Switzerland, which considers it right to build only power plants of the last generation.
On the contrary, the UK, Finland, Poland, the Czech Republic, the Netherlands, Sweden, South Africa, China, India, Brazil, to quote at least some countries, continue with determination in their projects.
After Fukushima, the United States decided to expand its fleet by one unit by restoring the construction of one power plant interrupted after the Three Mile Island power plant accident.
If the German model based on renewable energy is ever presented as an example, reality contradicts it.
The choice of Berlin will result in an increase in the price of electricity, increased energy dependence on gas imported especially from Russia, and a sharp increase in CO2 emissions caused by the construction of natural gas and coal power plants.
All these unpleasant effects will be felt within a few months.
The case of Denmark deserves to be considered.
The European champion in wind power, which accounts for 30% of its electricity, is also one of the largest consumers of coal and gas due to wind irregularities, which is why CO2 emissions and Danish electricity prices are 65% and 50% higher, respectively, than the European average.
On the contrary, thanks to the immutability of our energy policy, our neighbours will pay an electricity bill 40% higher than the payment of French households.
While in a globalised economy, energy costs are a key factor in competitiveness and a guarantee of maintaining industry on national territory, French businesses enjoy the benefits of the cheapest electricity in Europe.
For this reason, any significant reduction in the share of nuclear energy would cause a strong increase in the price of electricity, which would make illusory beautiful statements about the re-industrialization of our country and the defense of purchasing power.
The price that the vast majority of French people refuse to pay, just as they do not fundamentally oppose this energy, as polls show.
Recall that our country's energy policy has made it possible to build a sector with 125,000 direct jobs and 410,000 downstream jobs.
A highly-exporting sector brings a large number of small and medium-sized specialised firms to international markets, creating jobs that cannot be transferred abroad.
If France decided to leave the core, it would sacrifice a considerable number of these small and medium-sized enterprises and lose <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>6 billion a year that the country receives for exporting nuclear equipment and services.
Which power plant owner would order a nuclear reactor designed to operate for 60 years while its manufacturer is scheduled to go bankrupt?
When solving the energy equation, it must be admitted that there is no magical source for energy production, let alone that there is no diabolical one.
The development of low-carbon, nuclear and renewable energy equipment by the French industrial group AREVA demonstrates the complementarity of energy sources.
In the case of nuclear energy, it is an absolute necessity to maintain the highest level of safety.
In France, we have the State Office for Nuclear Safety, which carries out uncompromising and transparent supervision of existing nuclear power plants as well as the construction of a new power plant in Flamanville.
Our teams, whose professionalism is recognized, have the idea of safety in their blood.
In 50 years, the nuclear industry has suffered three major accidents.
The only one in Three Mile Island took place under normal operating conditions and was left without human casualties and environmental consequences.
In Chernobyl, the drama was caused by reactor concepts and inexcusable human errors.
In the case of Fukushima, some seem to forget that the accident was the result of two natural disasters of unprecedented magnitude that caused the deaths of tens of thousands of people.
The nuclear industry will learn from this accident as it did from the previous two.
The fruit of this step and the cooperation between the French and German nuclear safety authorities, operators and designers, is that the EPR reactor is a concept capable of resisting such phenomena.
While all those who wish to build a nuclear power plant consider it, stopping its construction in Flamanville would be an excellent gift to AREVA’s and EDF’s competitors and pave the way for them to seize a leading position in nuclear development.
It is necessary and legitimate to seek the best energy solution for our country, but it would be irresponsible to let emotions, dogmas and machinations dominate a debate so crucial to the economic, social and financial situation of our country.
Is immigration a burden or an opportunity for the economy?
The immigration policy pursued under Nicolas Sarkozy has been criticized from different angles – the overcrowding of the police, the courts and the administration subjected to the numbering policy, the compatibility of this policy with the status of a “country of human rights” that France boasts of.
Recently, it was an administrative harassment targeting foreign students, which became topical when the interior minister (see the newspaper Libération of 23 May) declared that France "does not need foreign talents, masons and waitresses".
But so far, it has rarely been dissected from an economic angle.
It must be said that there is a fairly broad consensus between the left and the right in this area.
To the right, Jacques Chirac said in 1976 that "900,000 unemployed should not be a problem in a country where there are 2 million immigrant workers" and to the left, Michel Rocard, when he said in 1990 that France "cannot accept all the misery of the world".
The only difference is the degree of generosity.
In 2005, the fear of an invasion by hordes of Polish plumbers into French territory was shared right and left.
In both camps, immigrants are seen as a burden on the economy and French society.
The only difference lies in the degree of generosity we are willing to give to immigrants.
In his program, Fran<0xC3><0xA7>ois Hollande limits himself to banalities, stating that joint development will allow us to solve our "migration problem".
This idea of immigration as a burden and a problem may apply in elections, but it is very expensive economically.
As economists Ian Goldin and Geoffrey Cameron point out in their recently published paper synthesizing the latest knowledge on immigration (Exceptional People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Define Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, 352 p.): among specialists there is a broad consensus on the positive impact of migration movements on economic growth.
Reducing immigration is crippling growth and damaging employment.
Concerns about the impact of migrants are based on the idea that these people can replace French workers, especially the less skilled, and create pressure to reduce their wages.
But experience shows that, in fact, immigrants are much more of a complement than substitutes for French workers by performing jobs in sectors with a shortage of workers.
Low-skilled immigrants in sectors that do not attract French workers, and those most skilled in dynamic sectors where education is insufficient to supply jobs.
Positive Impact on Wages
Just as a surgeon will have difficulty working in a country where there is a shortage of anesthesiologists, these additions between Frenchmen and migrants cause the arrivals of immigrants to have a positive impact on the wages and employment of French workers.
Giovanni Peri calculated that a 1% increase in migration movements would cause real wages to rise between 0.6% and 0.9% in the long run.
And it does not take into account the fact that the diversity brought by immigrants contributes to thought formation and economic growth (the high proportion of naturalized immigrants among American Nobel Prize winners; Google, Intel, Paypal, eBay, and Yahoo were all founded by immigrants).
Migrants are also net contributors to social systems in European countries, with an average of 1% of the total budget.
For example, the World Labour Organisation estimates that in Germany, one migrant arriving at the age of 30 will make a net contribution (income minus expenditure) of <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>150,000 to public budgets in his or her lifetime.
Nicolas Sarkozy, at the beginning of his term in office, expressed the wish to reach for the missing percentages of growth "with prized teeth".
The teeth used to deter immigrants had the opposite effect.
Europe Invented Democracy, European Democracy Remains to Be Rethought
Democracy is a rare commodity and a very fragile commodity.
The European continent should remember this, because despite the fact that it was invented in Athens two thousand years ago, it experienced during the 20th century the tragedy of world wars, totalitarian regimes, the Holocaust, the gulags, but also Franco in Spain, Salazar in Portugal and colonels in Greece.
Some people might have believed that in order for democracy to triumph definitively over its enemies, it would be enough to make a choice and carry it out in the most direct way possible.
However, it is known from Napoleon that it was about ease of thinking.
Universal suffrage, while a necessary condition for democracy, is not a sufficient condition and can become an “instrument of oppression,” as the Republican philosopher Etienne Vacherot once said.
No, democracy requires much more: public space, public spirit, values, organization of separation and control of power, education, enlightenment, social and economic solidarity, justice.
The crisis of Europe that we are experiencing is an economic crisis, but it has been the same since the beginning of the crises of politics and democracy.
Admitting the error of a Greek yes-no referendum will have the value of a double revelation in this regard: the revelation of the need for a major return of political power, but also the revelation of a disturbing sense of its impossibility, of its inadequacy.
This ambivalence must be considered in order to be overcome.
The truth is that the front lines of the democratic struggle have shifted today, and that many of the Republican fighters are no longer firing in the right direction.
We can get nothing if we demand a series of national referenda, organised as necessary and disorganised.
Bianca exposed to a European absolute monarch or a bound-footed leap into the void of nationalist depth: what a choice for the citizen!
No, we do not want guillotine knives, but a common, full-fledged, peaceful and continuous exercise of choice and democracy, this time at European level.
There are no crises in Greece, Italy, Spain, Portugal - we would not even know where to stop - because the crisis is in Europe.
It is the whole of Europe that is bowing to the dictates of markets and credit rating agencies, which is suffering from its incapacity and its lack of solidarity.
It is the whole of Europe that is being humiliated on the international stage.
We are concerned about the transfer of sovereignty to Europe - but it is the whole of Europe that is slowly losing its sovereignty and with it each of its peoples.
The management of the European project of democratic sovereignty must be restored as a matter of urgency.
Because only together will Europeans be able to reduce the burden of their debts, get rid of the government of the markets and prepare the future by investing.
The way out of the crisis will presuppose decisions at European level that cannot be taken without full democratic legitimacy, otherwise it would lead us to disaster.
After long fighting against this proposal by the Socialists and Jacques Delors, everyone today is strongly demanding a European economic government.
Yes, I am.
But to think this without stronger political and democratic integration, and experienced as such by citizens, would be a new folly and a new dead end.
We need to take on a new stage of European construction.
In order to establish a republic in France, it was necessary to "be" republicans.
A revolution in the interests of the people could not be enough.
This lesson continues.
We need to build a Europe that is more economically integrated.
This can only be done by building a more politically democratic and genuine European democratic sovereignty.
Let us become Europeans to build Europe.
"Contactless" chip cards are spreading
In an optimistic atmosphere, the world fair of smart cards will open on Tuesday in Villepinte near Paris.
According to the Eurosmart cabinet, 2011 should end with an increase in global sales of microprocessor cards (bank cards, SIM-card phones) by 11% to more than 6 billion units.
The most significant is the segment of contactless technology, which allows you to pay in public transport or make purchases by simply approaching the card to the reader.
This year, 460 million smart cards are expected to be sold worldwide, up from 320 million a year earlier.
Their share is expected to rise further in 2012 (expected 580 million units) and reach approximately 10% of the total chip card market (6.925 million cards).
Having been in the tow of APEC countries for a long time, Europe is gaining ground in contactless payment.
Approximately 26 million Visa bank cards are already equipped with this feature and 75,000 payment terminals accept them.
In France, the beginnings are more modest: 400,000 contactless Visa cards were issued.
But large retail chains work for two.
Carrefour has released 2.5 million contactless Pass MasterCards this year.
In order to get a higher gear, banks need to equip their clients with them from now on.
“Two large French companies have committed to systematically distributing contactless bank cards to their clients in the future,” said Gérard Nébouy, CEO of Visa Europe France.
Banks are testing mobile payments
But this is only the first step towards the means of payment of the future: the mobile phone.
Today, only a small number of devices are equipped with Near Field Communication (NFC).
"They're running late."
"But their real expansion should take place next year."
“For 2012, we estimate their sales in the world at 80 to 120 million units,” explains Marc Bertin, President of Eurosmart.
But banks are already preparing ahead.
Crédit Agricole Bank announced yesterday the launch of a test in the city of Caen, which will last from December to June next year.
iPhone devices of approximately 200 clients and co-workers will be equipped with a case that allows contactless payments.
BPCE has a similar project in Strasbourg and Marseille.
And the Société Generale announced yesterday that it is preparing to introduce an offer allowing its clients to pay by mobile phone without touch.
The terrorist front stretches from the Sahara to Nigeria
Paris is concerned about ties between al-Qaeda in the Islamic Maghreb and the Boko Haram sect.
The long-standing suspicions that there are ties between the al-Qaeda terrorist group in the Islamic Maghreb (AQMI) and the Nigerian sect Boko Haram are confirmed.
On Sunday, Algeria’s Deputy Foreign Minister Abdelkader Messahel even admitted that Algeria had “gained certainty” from now on.
“The way the two organizations operate and intelligence reports show that there is a lot of cooperation between them,” he said.
Paris seems to have similar analyses.
An investigation into the kidnapping of two Frenchmen in Niger in January 2010 could help shed light on the connecting bridges.
After being kidnapped by AQMI members from a restaurant in Niamey, Antoine de Léocour and Vincent Delory were to be killed the following day at the same time as several of their captors in an operation carried out by special French units.
In the rubble after the intervention, French and Nigerian investigators had to find several phones with chips belonging to terrorists.
The Terrorist Axis
Analysis of the calls made leads to several people in Mali, Niger and Nigeria.
According to Radio France Internationale (RFI), investigators are particularly interested in two figures: one leads to a Nigerian who has been in Maiduguri for a long time, a city in northern Nigeria that is the cradle of Boko Haram, and the other to a man said to be close to AQMI and the sect.
“It’s progress, but there is no doubt that we need to wait for more convincing evidence before we start talking about operational cooperation between AQMI and Boko Haram.”
"But it's possible."
“We have known for years that the sect enjoys external financial and intellectual support and is increasingly active,” said Kunle Amuwo, a Nigerian investigator.
In recent months, this "support" has become more and more evident in Boko Haram's development and speeches or in its operational procedures, which now include human casualties or increasingly complex explosive devices of the same design as those used by AQMI.
The international community, led by Washington, has since put pressure on Nigeria to take into account the problems posed by Boko Haram.
In fact, the Nigerian authorities have long regarded the group as a community of enlightened mystics of little interest.
Fast success
The Boko Haram sect was founded in 2002 in Maiduguri around the mosque, school and fundamentalist Mohammed Yusuf. Boko Haram, which in Haoussa language means "Western education is a sin", approves the establishment of an Islamic emirate in the Muslim north of Nigeria.
In this poor region, such a connection has rapid success.
The sect is politicized and requires strict adherence to Islamic sharia law, while its adherents launch a fight against the central government.
These people focus first on churches, bars, and offices.
In 2009, Boko Haram supporters became extremely active and multiplied their attacks against police stations.
As usual, the government’s response remains the same.
The army encircles the city, resulting in 800 deaths.
The founder of the sect, Mohammed Yusuf, is captured and killed in prison.
Since then, the group has been radicalized and is leaving its place of work in the north.
On Christmas Day 2010 in the city of Jos, an assassination attempt kills 80 people, then another in the capital Abuja.
In June, it is again in Abuja, where Boko Haram will attack the police headquarters in its first suicide attack.
And in August, the local UN office will be the first international target.
The creation of a terrorist axis in Africa, which should lead from Mauritania through Nigeria to Somalia, worries all security specialists from now on.
Now that al-Qaeda in the Islamic Maghreb has encircled Mali and the games and Somalis of the al-Shabaab movement are operating in Kenya, Boko Haram is emerging as a new threat to the continent.
Last week in Nigeria, during an interview with President Goodluck Jonathan, Alain Juppé said France was on alert and ready to "hand over all information".
