Nord Stream, a new port of entry for Russian gas to Europe
The Nord Stream gas pipeline, which connects Eastern Europe directly to Russia and runs along the bottom of the Baltic Sea, has begun to operate.
It must supply gas equivalent to 30 million households.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, wanted to properly celebrate this event.
More than 500 guests, including four heads of state and government, attended the inauguration of Nord Stream, a new gas pipeline that will connect Russia and Germany directly under the sea.
Symbolically, German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitry Medvedev, French Prime Minister Fran<0xC3><0xA7>ois Fillon and his Dutch counterpart Mark Rutte have turned together the control valve that controls the entry of Russian gas into the Western European network.
With this new gas pipeline, 27.5 billion additional cubic meters of Russian gas will flow annually to Western Europe via the 1,224 km long pipeline connecting the St. Petersburg region with the federal state of Mecklenburg-Vorpommern.
The second pipeline, due to be completed at the end of 2012, will allow a total of 55 billion cubic metres of gas to be supplied, an amount equal to the entire French consumption.
And it is already recalled the possibility of building a third pipeline on the same route.
For Gazprom, the timely completion of this huge construction has the character of a victory.
Poland and the Baltic states strongly protested against the project.
In fact, Nord Stream will make it possible to supply gas directly to Germany without being routed by a third country (Poland or Ukraine).
At the same time, these two countries are losing a bit of power: the ability to pressure Russia with threats to close its access to Western European markets is becoming more difficult for them.
Warsaw expressed this most strongly when it did not hesitate to compare the Nord Stream to the “new German-Soviet pact”, with reference to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin during the occupation of Poland in 1939.
It means to say that this is a politically sensitive topic.
Western Europe, through its support for this Russian project, has gained greater confidence in its purchases.
But this is at the cost of weakening Europe’s energy, because the project has created rifts between Europeans from the east and the west.
Just five years ago, Russia managed to assert its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich, gas-consuming Western countries whose deposits are nearing their end.
"This pipeline is part of our partnership with Russia, a new artery that organically connects us," Fillon said at the opening ceremony, demonstrating the extent to which large gas contracts are both political and economic.
All this explains the wide smiles of Gazprom’s leaders present in large numbers in Lubmin, the gas supply point.
The construction of this pipeline is also an important technical act.
The submarine pipeline is made of steel with a concrete casing to protect it from the anchors of sea vessels.
It rests at the bottom of the sea at an average depth of 200 m.
During its construction it was necessary to avoid minefields dating from the Second World War.
“For security reasons, almost a hundred of them had to be removed or destroyed,” said Jens M<0xC3><0xBC>ller, a spokesman for Nord Stream.
It was also necessary to increase measures for the protection of fauna and flora.
The pipe itself is a long metal snake weighing as much as 242 Eiffel Towers, which is not interrupted anywhere in its entire length by either valves or maintenance stations.
One control platform was to be built near Sweden, but the project leaders rejected it when the Swedes were only a little eager to see Russian state society settle permanently off their coast.
“In the event of a malfunction, we will stop the gas flow in less than 1 minute,” says Jens M<0xC3><0xBC>ller.
In the event of leakage, the gas contained in the pipeline escapes into the air.
But this case is considered unlikely by the builder, because the welds were designed to leak once every 100,000 years.
The condition of the pipeline from the outside is checked by an underwater robot towed by a ship, while the inside of the pipeline is checked by a device that circulates inside.
This cigar-shaped device with a diameter of 1 meter is introduced into the inside of the pipe and is pushed by gas.
At the finish line, after a full three days of travel at a speed of 3 m/s, it will provide accurate information on possible deformations of metal parts.
The long-distance gas pipeline was designed to operate for fifty years without the slightest need for repair.
The gas circulation is simply ensured by pressure.
The value of this pressure is 200 bar at the start and 100 bar at the finish.
Five companies have joined forces to implement this project.
The leading position remains held by Gazprom, which holds a 51% stake.
It was joined by the German companies E.ON and BASF (15.5 % each), as well as the Dutch company Gasunie and the French group GDF Suez (9% each).
The five companies set up a joint venture called Nord Stream to build and operate the pipeline.
The company is headquartered in Zoug, Switzerland, where taxation is extremely advantageous.
Gazprom subsequently leased to this company for five years a contract that can be renewed, all of its capacity for gas transportation.
“Gazprom will profit from the total capacity, no matter how much gas is actually transported,” says Jens M<0xC3><0xBC>ller.
The financing of the construction of the pipeline was secured by 30% of shareholders and 70% by bank loans.
The total cost of the works should reach 7.4 billion euros for both pipelines.
For the GDF Suez Group, investment costs have risen to 240 million.
But minority shareholders are confident that their costs will be reimbursed, since only Gazprom takes the risk.
The pipeline rises from the Baltic Sea in Lubmin on a sandy coast with pine forests.
Valves 4.5 meters high form the gas outlet gate.
The sensors measure the pressure, temperature and other characteristics of the incoming gas before it is transported to German gas pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, the terminal has been receiving one million cubic meters of Russian gas every hour.
At full capacity, it will be 3 million per hour and 6 million in 2012.
Moleskine - Brand Notebook
The Italian company Moleskine, which was founded fifty years ago, wants to once again provide the joy of writing.
It brings the scent of adventure, hours spent writing by candlelight.
Moleskine notebook is easily recognizable by its black rectangular plates and its leaves faded white color as if aged over time.
After all, the Moleskine notebook, as we know it today, was born in 1997.
At that time, the Italian company Modo Modo, based in Milan, decided to launch a new design, but distinguished notebook.
Maria Sebregondi, then a consultant working for the company, takes over the launch of the new product.
The notebook is inspired by the old production technique "moleskin" (imitation of leather), which is used, for example, for the surface treatment of benches.
This type of notebook was greatly appreciated by writers and travelers.
“Moleskine has returned to the old and forgotten subject that was an icon of avant-garde artists until the 20th century,” says Maria Sebregondi, who has since become the brand’s leader at Modo Modo.
Success is here.
Between 2006 and 2010, sales rose 26% to settle at 12.7 million units last year.
The situation is remote from the secret production from the first years, when only 3,000 notebooks were made.
Moleskine crosses the Italian border and is exported to 70 countries from France to the United States.
It is difficult to draw any artificial portrait of the buyer, because the notebook will attract a businessman as well as a student or professionals.
Moleskine’s image is that its owners are cosmopolitan, cultured and open-minded people.
The small Italian company, which had 12 employees in its beginnings, today has almost a hundred and since 2008 has two offices, one in Milan and the other in New York.
He sent his notebooks to bookstores and through the FNAC chain of stores to small boutiques in the middle of cities where he could assert his identity.
“We have been following the spirit of the times and this need for new writing, despite the stormy development of emails,” explains Maria Sebregondi.
This cultural signature accompanies the development of the Moleskine notebook: the brand has recently opened the exhibition "Zacházka", where architects or artists exhibit their notebook.
In August, on the occasion of the Locarno Film Festival, she also introduced new notebooks resembling a leopard.
Moleskine capitalizes on its success and this cultural aura and diversified its products: bags, diaries, pencils, laptop cases... The brand is expanding to a whole range of carriers.
An enviable success: in the fall of 2006, Modo Modo was bought by investment funds from SG Capital Europe, today Syntegra Capital, writing a new page in Moleskine history.
Why is there such a high proportion of unemployed disabled workers?
About 19% of people with disabilities are looking for work.
Today opens the 15th week for the employment of the disabled.
Despite the voluntary public policy introduced in 2005, the percentage of unemployed persons with disabilities is still twice as high as the average, i.e. 19% compared to 9% for the entire population.
Is it depressing?
"No," says <0xC3><0x89>ric Blanchet, CEO of the Adapt Association, which organizes the Week for Employing People with Disabilities.
"The progress achieved in 15 years is remarkable."
"At that time, the unemployment rate was not twice as high, but three times as high."
"Nevertheless, there is still much to be done."
It must be said that there are numerous obstacles for unemployed disabled persons before they can get to work.
These are the elderly: 37% are over 50 years old (17% on average).
They have low qualifications: 80% do not have a high school diploma and out of 2.3 million university students, only 10,000 are disabled.
And finally - long-term unemployment is very widespread: 53% for the disabled, compared to 38% on average.
In short, these are the criteria that make it particularly difficult to return to work and which constitute the "core of the problem", according to Christian Grapin, CEO of the Tremplin Association, which was established in 1992 to help businesses recruit disabled workers.
So much for objective brakes.
It remains unsaid, ways of thinking that are certainly evolving, but too slowly.
A study conducted in April by the IMS-Entreprendre pour la Cité association found that interviewed managers had a "poor level of knowledge about disabled people" with "exaggerated notions of wheelchair users and mental or mental disabilities".
As a result, private enterprises with more than 20 employees are still far from reaching the target of employing 6% of disabled workers set by the 1987 law.
The last known figures, which come from 2008, give a state of 2.6%.
“We are now at around 3%,” says Pierre Blanc, CEO of Agefiph, an organisation charged with collecting fees from businesses that do not comply with the law.
This is evidenced by the number of "penalty" businesses, as well as the amounts paid, which dropped from 59,000 to 46,000 (and from 606 million to 480 million euros) between 2007 and 2011.
“The 2005 law, which increased contributions, created a strong pressure on businesses,” explains Pierre Blanc.
"But this improvement also demonstrates real awareness, especially in large enterprises."
According to the Ministry of Labour, only 59% of enterprises with 20 to 49 employees employ disabled workers, compared to 82% of enterprises with 100 to 199 employees.
